'''Spotify''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|s|p|ɒ|t|ɪ|f|aɪ}}; {{IPA-sv|ˈspɔ̂tːɪfaj|lang}}) is a [[List of companies of Sweden|Swedish]]<ref name="spotify1">{{Cite web |title=Contact |url=https://www.spotify.com/us/about-us/contact/ |access-date=20 February 2022 |publisher=Spotify |archive-date=9 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160709201431/https://www.spotify.com/us/about-us/contact/ |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Streaming media|audio streaming]] and media service provider founded on 23 April 2006 by [[Daniel Ek]] and [[Martin Lorentzon]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=14 October 2016 |title=Spotify UK revenues surge to almost £190m as mobile subscriptions take off |url=http://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/oct/14/spotify-uk-revenues-surge-to-almost-190m-as-mobile-subscriptions-take-off |access-date=6 August 2021 |website=The Guardian |language=en |archive-date=17 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220717195247/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/oct/14/spotify-uk-revenues-surge-to-almost-190m-as-mobile-subscriptions-take-off |url-status=live }}</ref> It is one of the largest [[music streaming service]] providers, with over 615 million monthly [[active users]], including 239 million paying subscribers, as of March 2024.<ref name="QFR" /><ref name="Spotify company info2">{{Cite web |date=31 March 2024 |title=Company Info |url=https://newsroom.spotify.com/company-info/ |access-date=2 February 2022 |website=Spotify For the Record |archive-date=30 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930060609/https://newsroom.spotify.com/company-info/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Spotify is listed (through a [[Luxembourg City]]-domiciled [[holding company]], '''Spotify Technology S.A.'''<ref name="sec" />) on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] in the form of [[American depositary receipt]]s.

Spotify offers [[Digital rights management|digital copyright restricted]] recorded audio content, including more than 100 million songs and six million podcast titles, from record labels and media companies.<ref name="Spotify company info2" /> As a [[freemium]] service, basic features are free with advertisements and limited control, while additional features, such as offline listening and commercial-free listening, are offered via paid [[Subscription business model|subscriptions]]. Users can search for music based on [[Musician|artist]], [[album]], or [[Music genre|genre]], and can create, edit, and share [[playlist]]s.

Spotify is available in most of [[Europe]], as well as [[Africa]], the [[Americas]], [[Asia]], and [[Oceania]], with a total availability in 184 markets.<ref>{{Cite web |title=About Spotify |url=https://newsroom.spotify.com/company-info/ |access-date=10 January 2022 |website=Spotify |language=en-US |archive-date=30 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930060609/https://newsroom.spotify.com/company-info/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Its users and subscribers are based largely in the [[US]] and Europe, jointly accounting for around 53% of users and 67% of revenue.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Spotify Q3 2022 investor presentation |url=https://s29.q4cdn.com/175625835/files/doc_financials/2022/q3/Q3-2022-Shareholder-Deck-FINAL-LOCKED.pdf |access-date=7 January 2023 |archive-date=23 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221123020252/https://s29.q4cdn.com/175625835/files/doc_financials/2022/q3/Q3-2022-Shareholder-Deck-FINAL-LOCKED.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> It has no presence in [[mainland China]] where the market is dominated by [[QQ Music]]. The service is available on most devices, including [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[macOS]], and [[Linux]] computers, [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] smartphones and tablets, [[Home automation|smart home]] devices such as the [[Amazon Echo]] and [[Google Nest]] lines of products, and [[digital media player]]s like [[Roku]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Spotify Music |url=https://channelstore.roku.com/details/19977/spotify |access-date=12 November 2018 |website=Roku Channel Store |publisher=Roku |archive-date=28 September 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200928012717/https://channelstore.roku.com/details/19977/spotify |url-status=live }}</ref> As of December 2023, Spotify was the [[List of most-visited websites|47th most-visited website in the world]] with 24.78% of its traffic coming from the United States followed by [[Brazil]] with 6.51% according to data provided by [[Semrush]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Top websites|url=https://www.semrush.com/trending-websites/global/all|website=Semrush|access-date=25 December 2023|archive-date=19 December 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231219181830/https://www.semrush.com/trending-websites/global/all|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.semrush.com/website/spotify.com/overview/?source=trending-websites|title=spotify.com|website=[[semrush]]|access-date=25 December 2023|archive-date=25 December 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231225141959/https://www.semrush.com/website/spotify.com/overview/?source=trending-websites|url-status=live}}</ref>

Unlike physical or download sales, which pay artists a fixed price per song or album sold, Spotify pays [[royalties]] based on the number of artist streams as a proportion of total songs streamed. It distributes approximately 70% of its total revenue to rights holders (often [[record label]]s), who then pay artists based on individual agreements.<ref name=":22">{{Cite news |last=Sehgal |first=Kabir |date=26 January 2018 |title=Spotify and Apple Music should become record labels so musicians can make a fair living |work=CNBC |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/01/26/how-spotify-apple-music-can-pay-musicians-more-commentary.html |access-date=21 November 2018 |archive-date=24 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224043025/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/01/26/how-spotify-apple-music-can-pay-musicians-more-commentary.html |url-status=live }}</ref> While certain musicians have voiced objections to Spotify's royalty structure and its effect on record sales, others laud the service for offering a lawful option to combat piracy and for remunerating artists each time their music is played.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Swanson |first=Kate |date=2013 |title=A Case Study on Spotify: Exploring Perceptions of the Music Streaming Service |url=http://www.meiea.org/Journal/Vol13/Swanson |journal=Journal of the Music and Entertainment Industry Educators Association |volume=13 |issue=1 |pages=207–230 |doi=10.25101/13.10 |doi-access=free |access-date=5 November 2023 |archive-date=1 December 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231201024516/https://www.meiea.org/Journal/Vol13/Swanson |url-status=live }}</ref> 
{{Toclimit|3}}

== History ==
Spotify was founded in 2006 in [[Stockholm]], Sweden,<ref>{{Cite news |date=2 March 2018 |title=The story of Spotify: Sweden's controversial king of music streaming |work=The Local Sweden |url=https://www.thelocal.se/20180302/the-story-of-spotify-swedens-controversial-king-of-music-streaming |access-date=31 May 2020 |archive-date=2 June 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200602210017/https://www.thelocal.se/20180302/the-story-of-spotify-swedens-controversial-king-of-music-streaming |url-status=live }}</ref> by [[Daniel Ek]], former [[Chief technology officer|CTO]] of [[Stardoll]], and Martin Lorentzon, co-founder of [[Tradedoubler]].<ref name="Parsons">{{Cite web |last=Parsons |first=Jeff |date=3 April 2018 |title=History of Spotify: how the Swedish streaming company changed the music industry |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tech/history-spotify-how-swedish-streaming-12291542 |access-date=31 May 2020 |website=mirror |archive-date=3 June 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200603170642/https://www.mirror.co.uk/tech/history-spotify-how-swedish-streaming-12291542 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Huddleston Jr. |first=Tom |date=4 April 2018 |title=How Spotify's college-dropout founder became a self-made millionaire at 23 — and a billionaire at 35 |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/04/04/spotify-ceo-daniel-ek-is-a-billionaire-after-ipo.html |access-date=31 May 2020 |website=CNBC |archive-date=3 December 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201203054502/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/04/04/spotify-ceo-daniel-ek-is-a-billionaire-after-ipo.html |url-status=live }}</ref> According to Ek, the company's title was initially misheard from a name shouted by Lorentzon. Later they conceived a [[portmanteau]] of "spot" and "identify".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bertoni |first=Steven |title=Spotify's Daniel Ek: The Most Important Man In Music |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/stevenbertoni/2012/01/04/spotifys-daniel-ek-the-most-important-man-in-music/ |access-date=31 May 2020 |website=Forbes |archive-date=18 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190418112652/https://www.forbes.com/sites/stevenbertoni/2012/01/04/spotifys-daniel-ek-the-most-important-man-in-music/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Early international launches ===
[[File:Daniel Ek addressing Spotify staff.jpg|thumb|Daniel Ek addressing Spotify staff in 2010]]
[[File:Spotify HQ.jpg|thumb|Former Spotify headquarters in Stockholm]]
In February 2010, Spotify opened public registration for the free service tier in the United Kingdom.<ref name="Parsons" /> Registrations surged following the release of the mobile service, leading Spotify to halt registration for the free service in September, returning the UK to an invitation-only policy.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Spotify reintroduces waiting list, nudges you to paying |url=https://www.theregister.com/2009/09/11/spotify_signups/ |access-date=31 May 2020 |website=www.theregister.com |archive-date=3 August 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200803132131/https://www.theregister.com/2009/09/11/spotify_signups/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Spotify launched in the United States in July 2011, and offered a six-month, ad-supported trial period, during which new users could listen to an unlimited amount of music for free. In January 2012, the free trial periods began to expire, limiting users to ten hours of streaming each month and five plays per song.<ref>{{Cite web |last=D'Orazio |first=Dante |date=6 January 2012 |title=Spotify early adopters will soon lose unlimited listening on free accounts |url=https://www.theverge.com/2012/1/6/2688250/spotify-free-account-restriction-10-hours-per-month |access-date=31 May 2020 |website=The Verge |archive-date=5 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210205091312/https://www.theverge.com/2012/1/6/2688250/spotify-free-account-restriction-10-hours-per-month |url-status=live }}</ref> Using PC streaming, a similar structure to the one used today allowed the listener to play songs freely, but with ads every 4–7 songs depending on listening duration. Later that same year, in March, Spotify removed all limits on the free service tier indefinitely, including mobile devices.<ref>{{Cite web |date=29 March 2012 |title=Spotify to continue to let US users stream music for free |url=https://nypost.com/2012/03/29/spotify-to-continue-to-let-us-users-stream-music-for-free/ |access-date=31 May 2020 |website=New York Post |archive-date=2 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210202185704/https://nypost.com/2012/03/29/spotify-to-continue-to-let-us-users-stream-music-for-free/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In April 2016, Ek and Lorentzon wrote an open letter to Swedish politicians, demanding action in three areas that they claimed hindered the company's ability to recruit top talent as Spotify grew, including access to flexible housing, better education in the programming and development fields, and stock options. Ek and Lorentzon wrote that to continue competing in a global economy, politicians needed to respond with new policies, or thousands of Spotify jobs would be moved from Sweden to the United States.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Sheffield |first=Hazel |date=15 April 2016 |title=Spotify's threats to leave Sweden spur startup protest in Stockholm |work=[[The Independent]] |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/spotifys-threats-to-leave-sweden-spur-startup-protest-in-stockholm-a6986431.html |url-status=live |url-access=subscription |access-date=11 December 2017 |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220524/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/spotifys-threats-to-leave-sweden-spur-startup-protest-in-stockholm-a6986431.html |archive-date=24 May 2022}}</ref>

In February 2017, Spotify announced the expansion of its United States operations in [[Lower Manhattan]], New York City, at [[4 World Trade Center]], adding approximately 1,000 new jobs and retaining 832 existing positions.<ref>{{Cite web |date=15 February 2017 |title=Spotify expands with World Trade Center move |url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/business/02/16/17/spotify-expands-with-world-trade-center-move |access-date=15 February 2017 |publisher=Agence France-Presse via ABS-CBN |archive-date=16 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216024956/http://news.abs-cbn.com/business/02/16/17/spotify-expands-with-world-trade-center-move |url-status=live }}</ref> The company's US headquarters are in New York City's [[Flatiron District]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Loudenback |first=Tanza |date=25 July 2016 |title=Step inside Spotify's New York City office, where you'll find an airy roof deck, cold brew coffee, and a secret recording studio |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/spotify-office-tour-2016-7 |access-date=19 February 2017 |website=[[Business Insider]] |archive-date=20 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170220094011/http://www.businessinsider.com/spotify-office-tour-2016-7 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 14 November 2018, the company announced 13 new markets in the [[MENA]] region, including the creation of a new Arabic hub and several playlists.<ref>{{Cite news |date=17 November 2021 |title=Spotify expands to Iraq and Libya |work=Arab News |url=https://arab.news/naj9n}}</ref>

=== Other developments ===
==== Streaming records ====
{{Main|List of most-streamed artists on Spotify|List of Spotify streaming records}}

In October 2015, "[[Thinking Out Loud]]" by [[Ed Sheeran]] became the first song to pass 500 million streams.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Weiner |first=Natalie |date=12 October 2015 |title=Ed Sheeran's 'Thinking Out Loud' Becomes First Song to Hit 500 Million Spotify Streams |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6723002/ed-sheeran-thinking-out-loud-spotify-500-million-streams |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=13 November 2016 |archive-date=13 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113190903/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6723002/ed-sheeran-thinking-out-loud-spotify-500-million-streams |url-status=live }}</ref> A month later, Spotify announced that "[[Lean On]]" by [[Major Lazer]] and [[DJ Snake]] featuring [[MØ]] was its most-streamed song of all time with over 525 million streams worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web |date=12 November 2015 |title=Leaning power: Spotify names its most streamed track of all time |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/nov/12/spotify-most-streamed-track-all-time-major-lazer-lean-on |access-date=13 November 2016 |website=[[The Guardian]] |archive-date=3 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803052949/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/nov/12/spotify-most-streamed-track-all-time-major-lazer-lean-on |url-status=live }}</ref> In April 2016, [[Rihanna]] overtook [[Justin Bieber]] to become the biggest artist on Spotify, with 31.3 million monthly active listeners.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Ingham |first=Tim |date=7 April 2016 |title=The biggest artist on Spotify is a shareholder in Tidal |url=http://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/biggest-artist-spotify-shareholder-tidal |access-date=13 November 2016 |website=Music Business Worldwide |archive-date=30 September 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160930192929/http://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/biggest-artist-spotify-shareholder-tidal/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In May 2016, Rihanna was overtaken by [[Drake (musician)|Drake]] with 31.85 million monthly listeners.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Jones |first=Rhian |date=18 May 2016 |title=Drake is Spotify's most popular artist in history ... and right now |url=http://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/drake-is-spotifys-most-popular-artist-in-history-and-right-now/ |access-date=19 December 2016 |website=Music Business Worldwide |archive-date=20 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220183535/http://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/drake-is-spotifys-most-popular-artist-in-history-and-right-now/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In December 2016, Drake's just-under 36 million monthly listeners were overtaken by the [[The Weeknd|Weeknd]]'s 36.068 million.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Ingham |first=Tim |date=1 December 2016 |title=Drake finally loses his Spotify crown to record-breaking The Weeknd |url=http://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/drake-finally-loses-his-crown-on-spotifys-to-record-breaking-the-weeknd/ |access-date=19 December 2016 |website=Music Business Worldwide |archive-date=20 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220183955/http://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/drake-finally-loses-his-crown-on-spotifys-to-record-breaking-the-weeknd/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Later that same month, Drake's song "[[One Dance]]" became the first song to hit one billion streams on Spotify.<ref>{{Cite web |last=McIntyre |first=Hugh |date=16 December 2016 |title=Drake's ''One Dance'' Is The First Song To Hit 1 Billion Plays On Spotify |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2016/12/16/drakes-one-dance-is-the-first-song-to-hit-1-billion-plays-on-spotify/ |access-date=19 December 2016 |website=[[Forbes]] |archive-date=17 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161217113530/http://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2016/12/16/drakes-one-dance-is-the-first-song-to-hit-1-billion-plays-on-spotify/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Kaufman |first=Gil |date=16 December 2016 |title=Drake's ''One Dance'' Is First Song to Reach 1 Billion Plays on Spotify |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/7625179/drake-one-dance-spotify-first-1-billion-plays |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=19 December 2016 |archive-date=24 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224025543/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/7625179/drake-one-dance-spotify-first-1-billion-plays |url-status=live }}</ref> Upon its release in August 2017, the single "[[Look What You Made Me Do]]" by [[Taylor Swift]] earned over eight million streams within 24 hours, breaking the record for the most single-day streams for a track.<ref>{{Cite web |date=26 August 2017 |title=Taylor Swift sets records for Spotify streams and platforms, YouTube views |url=https://www.apnews.com/54b87ebc88bd4565bd3bb1622970e6d9 |access-date=7 September 2017 |website=[[The Associated Press]] |archive-date=10 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170910083152/https://www.apnews.com/54b87ebc88bd4565bd3bb1622970e6d9 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 19 June 2018, [[XXXTentacion]]'s hit single "[[Sad!]]" broke Swift's single-day streaming record, amassing 10.4 million streams the day after he was [[Killing of XXXTentacion|fatally shot]] in Florida.<ref>{{Cite magazine |title=XXXTentacion Breaks Taylor Swift's Single-Day Streaming Record on Spotify |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8461986/xxxtentacion-spotify-streaming-record-day-taylor-swift |magazine=Billboard |access-date=14 January 2020 |archive-date=21 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621023757/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8461986/xxxtentacion-spotify-streaming-record-day-taylor-swift |url-status=live }}</ref>

==== User growth ====
In March 2011, Spotify announced a customer base of 1 million paying subscribers across Europe,<ref>{{Cite web |date=8 March 2011 |title=Spotify hits milestone with 1 million subscribers |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-12676327 |access-date=7 November 2016 |website=BBC News |publisher=BBC |archive-date=9 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190109043226/https://www.bbc.com/news/business-12676327 |url-status=live }}</ref> and by September 2011, the number of paying subscribers had doubled to two million.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Van Grove |first=Jennifer |date=21 September 2011 |title=Spotify Surpasses 2 Million Paying Subscribers |url=http://mashable.com/2011/09/21/spotify-2-million-subscribers/ |access-date=7 November 2016 |website=[[Mashable]] |archive-date=1 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701075841/https://mashable.com/2011/09/21/spotify-2-million-subscribers/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In August 2012, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' reported 15 million active users, four million being paying Spotify subscribers.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Sanburn |first=Josh |date=16 August 2012 |title=Spotify is Growing — But Why Isn't It Growing Faster? |url=http://business.time.com/2012/08/16/spotify-is-growing-but-the-idea-of-music-ownership-is-holding-it-back/ |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |access-date=7 November 2016 |archive-date=6 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206123951/http://business.time.com/2012/08/16/spotify-is-growing-but-the-idea-of-music-ownership-is-holding-it-back/ |url-status=live }}</ref> User growth continued, reaching 20 million total active users, including five million paying customers globally and one million paying customers in the United States, in December 2012.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Weber |first=Harrison |date=6 December 2012 |title=Spotify announces 5M+ paid subscribers globally, 1M paid in US, 20M total active users, 1B playlists |url=https://thenextweb.com/insider/2012/12/06/spotify-announces/ |access-date=7 November 2016 |website=The Next Web |archive-date=30 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190630012414/https://thenextweb.com/insider/2012/12/06/spotify-announces/ |url-status=live }}</ref> By March 2013, the service had 24 million active users, six million being paying subscribers,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Sloan |first=Paul |date=29 May 2014 |title=Spotify: Growing like mad, yet so far to go |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/spotify-growing-like-mad-yet-so-far-to-go/ |access-date=7 November 2016 |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |archive-date=2 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402104036/https://www.cnet.com/news/spotify-growing-like-mad-yet-so-far-to-go/ |url-status=live }}</ref> which grew to 40 million users (including ten million paying) in May 2014,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Brustein |first=Joshua |date=22 May 2014 |title=Spotify Hits 10 Million Paid Users. Now Can It Make Money? |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-05-21/why-spotify-and-the-streaming-music-industry-cant-make-money |access-date=7 November 2016 |website=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |archive-date=2 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402102451/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-05-21/why-spotify-and-the-streaming-music-industry-cant-make-money |url-status=live }}</ref> 60 million users (including 15 million paying) in December 2014, 75 million users (20 million paying) in June 2015, 30 million paying subscribers in March 2016,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Singleton |first=Micah |date=21 March 2016 |title=Spotify hits 30 million subscribers |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/3/21/11220398/spotify-hits-30-million-subscribers |access-date=7 November 2016 |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |archive-date=26 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726125831/https://www.theverge.com/2016/3/21/11220398/spotify-hits-30-million-subscribers |url-status=live }}</ref> 40 million paying subscribers in September 2016,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Kahn |first=Jordan |date=14 September 2016 |title=Spotify hits 40 million paid subscriber milestone, outpacing Apple Music's growth |url=https://9to5mac.com/2016/09/14/spotify-40-million-subscribers/ |access-date=7 November 2016 |website=9to5Mac |archive-date=7 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190907014354/https://9to5mac.com/2016/09/14/spotify-40-million-subscribers/ |url-status=live }}</ref> and 100 million total users in June 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Murgia |first=Madhumita |date=20 June 2016 |title=Spotify crosses 100&nbsp;m users |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2016/06/20/spotify-crosses-100m-users/ |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2016/06/20/spotify-crosses-100m-users/ |archive-date=10 January 2022 |access-date=7 November 2016 |website=[[The Daily Telegraph]]}}{{cbignore}}</ref> In April 2020, Spotify reached 133 million premium users.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Spangler |first=Todd |date=29 April 2020 |title=Spotify Gains 6 Million Paid Subscribers in Q1 as COVID-19 Disrupts Listening Patterns |url=https://variety.com/2020/digital/news/spotify-q1-2020-gains-6-million-subscribers-coronavirus-1234592814/ |access-date=31 May 2020 |website=Variety |archive-date=27 May 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200527232703/https://variety.com/2020/digital/news/spotify-q1-2020-gains-6-million-subscribers-coronavirus-1234592814/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In countries affected by the [[COVID-19 pandemic]], Spotify registered a fall in users in late February, but it has seen a recovery.<ref>{{Cite web |date=29 April 2020 |title=Spotify's subscribers, usage surge amid coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/29/spotify-spot-earnings-q1-2020.html |access-date=30 April 2020 |website=CNBC |archive-date=29 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200429210254/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/29/spotify-spot-earnings-q1-2020.html |url-status=live }}</ref> In March 2022, Spotify had 182 million premium subscribers.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Spotify Q1 2022 financials reveal 182m subscribers and 422m active users – Music Ally |date=27 April 2022 |url=https://musically.com/2022/04/27/spotify-q1-2022-financials/ |access-date=27 July 2022 |archive-date=27 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220427102054/https://musically.com/2022/04/27/spotify-q1-2022-financials/ |url-status=live }}</ref> At the end of Q2 2022, Spotify reported 188 million paying subscribers and 433 million total users.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Porter |first=Jon |date=27 July 2022 |title=Spotify's subscribers rise to 188M amid podcasting setbacks |url=https://www.theverge.com/2022/7/27/23280283/spotify-q2-2022-earnings-podcasting-audiobooks |access-date=27 July 2022 |website=The Verge |language=en |archive-date=27 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220727103619/https://www.theverge.com/2022/7/27/23280283/spotify-q2-2022-earnings-podcasting-audiobooks |url-status=live }}</ref>

==== Premium-exclusive albums ====
The ''[[Financial Times]]'' reported in March 2017 that, as part of its efforts to renegotiate new licensing deals with music labels, Spotify and major record labels had agreed that Spotify would restrict some newly released albums to its Premium tier, with Spotify receiving a reduction in royalty fees to do so. Select albums would be available only on the Premium tier for a period of time, before general release. The deal "may be months away from being finalized, but Spotify is said to have cleared this particular clause with major record labels".<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Statt |first1=Nick |last2=Singleton |first2=Micah |date=16 March 2017 |title=Spotify will restrict some albums to its paid tier |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/3/16/14950492/spotify-premium-free-tier-restricting-album-releases-ipo |access-date=17 March 2017 |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |archive-date=16 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316225238/http://www.theverge.com/2017/3/16/14950492/spotify-premium-free-tier-restricting-album-releases-ipo |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Wilhelm |first=Parker |date=16 March 2017 |title=Spotify may soon require a Premium account to listen to certain albums |url=http://www.techradar.com/news/spotify-may-soon-require-a-premium-account-to-listen-to-certain-albums |access-date=17 March 2017 |website=[[TechRadar]] |archive-date=17 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317033320/http://www.techradar.com/news/spotify-may-soon-require-a-premium-account-to-listen-to-certain-albums |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Summers |first=Nick |date=16 March 2017 |title=Spotify might delay album releases for 'free' users |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/03/16/spotify-might-delay-album-releases-for-free-users/ |access-date=17 March 2017 |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=AOL |archive-date=17 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317000759/https://www.engadget.com/2017/03/16/spotify-might-delay-album-releases-for-free-users/ |url-status=live }}</ref> New reports in April confirmed that Spotify and [[Universal Music Group]] had reached an agreement to allow artists part of Universal to limit their new album releases to the Premium service tier for a maximum of two weeks. Spotify CEO Daniel Ek commented that "We know that not every album by every artist should be released the same way, and we've worked hard with UMG to develop a new, flexible release policy. Starting today, Universal artists can choose to release new albums on premium only for two weeks, offering subscribers an earlier chance to explore the complete creative work, while the singles are available across Spotify for all our listeners to enjoy".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Singleton |first=Micah |date=4 April 2017 |title=Spotify Premium users will get some albums two weeks before free users |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/4/4/15177004/spotify-premium-two-week-exclusive-albums-licensing-universal-music-group |access-date=5 April 2017 |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |archive-date=4 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404234938/http://www.theverge.com/2017/4/4/15177004/spotify-premium-two-week-exclusive-albums-licensing-universal-music-group |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Titcomb |first=James |date=4 April 2017 |title=Spotify to restrict albums to paying subscribers for first time |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2017/04/04/spotify-restrict-albums-paying-subscribers-first-time/ |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2017/04/04/spotify-restrict-albums-paying-subscribers-first-time/ |archive-date=10 January 2022 |access-date=5 April 2017 |website=[[The Daily Telegraph]]}}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Hern |first=Alex |date=4 April 2017 |title=Spotify to host top stars' albums for premium subscribers only |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/apr/04/spotify-universal-albums-premium-subscribers-only |access-date=5 April 2017 |website=[[The Guardian]] |archive-date=4 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404203828/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/apr/04/spotify-universal-albums-premium-subscribers-only |url-status=live }}</ref> It was announced later in April that this type of agreement would be extended to [[Indie music scene|indie]] artists signed to the [[Merlin Network]] agency.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Schneider |first=Marc |date=20 April 2017 |title=Following Universal Deal, Spotify Locks Down Indies in Long-Term Licensing Pact With Merlin |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7767810/spotify-merlin-licensing-agreement-indies |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=20 April 2017 |archive-date=21 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170421065905/http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7767810/spotify-merlin-licensing-agreement-indies |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Ingraham |first=Nathan |date=20 April 2017 |title=Spotify lets thousands of indie labels limit free streaming |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/04/20/spotify-merlin-records-limited-free-streaming/ |access-date=20 April 2017 |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=AOL |archive-date=20 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420184327/https://www.engadget.com/2017/04/20/Spotify-Merlin-records-limited-free-streaming/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

==== Direct public offering ====
Spotify went public on the [[stock market]] in April 2018 using a [[direct public offering]] rather than an [[initial public offering]]. This approach is not intended to raise fresh capital, but to let investors get their returns.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news |date=1 March 2018 |title=Is Spotify really worth $23bn? |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-43235317 |access-date=1 March 2018 |archive-date=28 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228231416/http://www.bbc.com/news/business-43235317 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Spotify files to go public as it discloses subscriber growth and heavy losses |work=The Verge |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/28/16846064/spotify-ipo-public-offering-announced-music-streaming |access-date=1 March 2018 |archive-date=28 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228225025/https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/28/16846064/spotify-ipo-public-offering-announced-music-streaming |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite news |last=Castillo |first=Michelle |date=28 February 2018 |title=Spotify files to go public, lost $1.5 billion last year |work=CNBC |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/02/28/spotify-files-for-ipo.html |access-date=1 March 2018 |archive-date=28 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228225209/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/02/28/spotify-files-for-ipo.html |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Morgan Stanley]] is the company's slated advisor on the matter.<ref name=":1" />

After making its debut on the New York Stock Exchange on 3 April 2018, [[CNBC]] reported that Spotify opened at $165.90, more than 25% above its reference price of $132.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Salinas |first=Sara |date=3 April 2018 |title=Spotify loses some of its initial heat as it drops from its opening price of $165.90 |work=CNBC |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/04/03/spotify-spot-ipo-stock-starts-trading-on-the-nyse.html |access-date=3 April 2018 |archive-date=3 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403183600/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/04/03/spotify-spot-ipo-stock-starts-trading-on-the-nyse.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

==== 2020 hacking incident ====
On 3 July 2020, [[Computer security|cybersecurity]] firm VPNMentor discovered a database containing 380 million individual records, including the logins and passwords of Spotify users.<ref>{{Cite news |date=24 November 2020 |title=Report: Spotify Targeted in Potential Fraud Scheme |work=vpnMentor |url=https://www.vpnmentor.com/blog/report-spotify-scam/ |access-date=2 December 2020 |archive-date=1 December 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201201170130/https://www.vpnmentor.com/blog/report-spotify-scam/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The database was thought to be evidence of an impending [[credential stuffing]] [[cyberattack]] targeting Spotify<ref>{{Cite news |last=Moore |first=Mike |date=24 November 2020 |title=Thousands of Spotify accounts hacked – here's what you need to know |work=TechRadar |url=https://www.techradar.com/news/thousands-of-spotify-accounts-hacked-heres-what-you-need-to-know |access-date=2 December 2020 |archive-date=29 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201129130639/https://www.techradar.com/news/thousands-of-spotify-accounts-hacked-heres-what-you-need-to-know |url-status=live }}</ref> as it contained the credentials of up to 350,000 compromised user accounts.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Owaida |first=Amer |date=24 November 2020 |title=Up to 350,000 Spotify accounts hacked in credential stuffing attacks |work=WeLiveSecurity |url=https://www.welivesecurity.com/2020/11/24/350000-spotify-accounts-hacked-credential-stuffing-attacks/ |access-date=2 December 2020 |archive-date=3 December 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201203002535/https://www.welivesecurity.com/2020/11/24/350000-spotify-accounts-hacked-credential-stuffing-attacks/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In response to the attack, Spotify issued a rolling reset of passwords for affected accounts in November 2020.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Woodard |first=Nick |date=26 November 2020 |title=300,000 Spotify Accounts Reportedly Hacked |work=ScreenRant |url=https://screenrant.com/spotify-accounts-data-stolen-major-hack-explained/ |access-date=2 December 2020 |archive-date=29 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201129160849/https://screenrant.com/spotify-accounts-data-stolen-major-hack-explained/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

==== Acquisitions, podcasting and exclusivity deals ====
In May 2013, Spotify acquired music discovery app Tunigo.<ref>{{Cite web |date=3 May 2013 |title=Spotify Acquires Music Discovery App Tunigo, A Spotify-Powered Songza Competitor |url=https://social.techcrunch.com/2013/05/03/spotify-acquires-music-discovery-app-tunigo-a-spotify-powered-songza-competitor/ }}{{Dead link|date=August 2023 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In March 2014, they acquired [[The Echo Nest]], a music intelligence company.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Etherington |first=Darrell |date=6 March 2014 |title=Spotify Acquires The Echo Nest, Gaining Control Of The Music DNA Company That Powers Its Rivals |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/03/06/spotify-acquires-the-echo-nest/ |access-date=13 November 2016 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |archive-date=13 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161113175717/https://techcrunch.com/2014/03/06/spotify-acquires-the-echo-nest/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=10 May 2015 |title=Turns Out Spotify Acquired The Echo Nest For Just €50M |url=https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/spotify-acquired-echo-nest-just-e50m/ |access-date=14 July 2020 |archive-date=6 June 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200606075145/https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/spotify-acquired-echo-nest-just-e50m/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In June 2015, Spotify announced they had acquired Seed Scientific, a data science consulting firm and [[analytics]] company. In a comment to [[TechCrunch]], Spotify said that Seed Scientific's team would lead an advanced analytics unit within the company, focused on developing data services.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Constine |first=Josh |date=24 June 2015 |title=Spotify Buys Beats' Analytics Provider Seed Scientific |url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/06/24/pulling-the-data-rug-out-from-under-apple/ |access-date=11 December 2016 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |archive-date=20 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220103334/https://techcrunch.com/2015/06/24/pulling-the-data-rug-out-from-under-apple/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Vanian |first=Jonathan |date=24 June 2015 |title=Why Spotify just bought a data science startup |url=http://fortune.com/2015/06/24/spotify-data-acquisition/ |access-date=11 December 2016 |website=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] . |archive-date=6 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206124339/http://fortune.com/2015/06/24/spotify-data-acquisition/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In January 2016, they acquired social and messaging startups Cord Project and Soundwave,<ref>{{Cite web |date=20 January 2016 |title=Spotify Buys Cord Project And Soundwave To Expand Messaging And Social Features |url=https://social.techcrunch.com/2016/01/20/spotify-buys-cord-project-and-soundwave/ }}{{Dead link|date=August 2023 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> followed in April 2016 by CrowdAlbum, a "startup that collects photos and videos of performances shared on social networks," and would "enhance the development of products that help artists understand, activate, and monetize their audiences".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Goldman |first=Joshua |date=27 April 2016 |title=Spotify snaps up photo-video aggregator for concertgoers |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/spotify-snaps-up-crowdalbum-photo-and-video-aggregator-for-concertgoers/ |access-date=4 February 2017 |website=CNET |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |archive-date=6 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206124025/https://www.cnet.com/news/spotify-snaps-up-crowdalbum-photo-and-video-aggregator-for-concertgoers/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In November 2016, Spotify acquired Preact, a "cloud-based platform and service developed for companies that operate on subscription models which helps reduce churn and build up their subscriber numbers".<ref>{{Cite web |date=2 November 2016 |title=Spotify acquires Preact to fuel its subscription business |url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/11/02/spotify-acquires-preact-to-boost-its-subscriber-story/ |access-date=15 September 2020 |publisher=Techcrunch |archive-date=29 September 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200929080822/https://techcrunch.com/2016/11/02/spotify-acquires-preact-to-boost-its-subscriber-story/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In March 2017, Spotify acquired Sonalytic, an audio detection startup, for an undisclosed amount of money. Spotify stated that Sonalytic would be used to improve the company's personalized playlists, better match songs with compositions, and improve the company's publishing data system.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Perez |first=Sarah |date=7 March 2017 |title=Spotify acquires audio detection startup Sonalytic |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/03/07/spotify-acquires-audio-detection-startup-sonalytic/ |access-date=15 March 2017 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |archive-date=15 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315174434/https://techcrunch.com/2017/03/07/spotify-acquires-audio-detection-startup-sonalytic/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Later that month, Spotify also acquired MightyTV, an app connected to television streaming services, including [[Netflix]] and [[HBO Go]], that recommends content to users. Spotify intended to use MightyTV to improve its advertising efforts on the free tier of service.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Ingham |first=Tim |date=27 March 2017 |title=Spotify acquires MightyTV. Can its founder fix Daniel Ek's advertising woes? |url=https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/spotify-acquires-mightytv-can-its-founder-fix-daniel-eks-advertising-woes/ |access-date=5 May 2017 |website=Music Business Worldwide |archive-date=30 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170330181345/http://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/spotify-acquires-mightytv-can-its-founder-fix-daniel-eks-advertising-woes/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In April 2017, they acquired Mediachain, a [[blockchain]] startup that had been developing a [[Decentralized computing|decentralized database]] system for managing attribution, and other [[metadata]] for media.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Perez |first=Sarah |date=26 April 2017 |title=Spotify acquires blockchain startup Mediachain to solve music's attribution problem |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/04/26/spotify-acquires-blockchain-startup-mediachain-to-solve-musics-attribution-problem/ |access-date=27 April 2017 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |archive-date=27 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427025019/https://techcrunch.com/2017/04/26/spotify-acquires-blockchain-startup-mediachain-to-solve-musics-attribution-problem/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=LeFebvre |first=Rob |date=26 April 2017 |title=Spotify's latest move shows it's trying to get royalties right |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/04/26/spotify-acquisition-royalties/ |access-date=27 April 2017 |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=AOL |archive-date=27 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427013541/https://www.engadget.com/2017/04/26/spotify-acquisition-royalties/ |url-status=live }}</ref> This was followed in May 2017 with the acquisition of [[artificial intelligence]] startup Niland, which uses technology to improve personalisation and recommendation features for users.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Russell |first=Jon |date=18 May 2017 |title=Spotify buys AI startup Niland to develop its music personalization and recommendations |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/05/18/spotify-buys-ai-startup-niland/ |access-date=20 May 2017 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |archive-date=20 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170520051416/https://techcrunch.com/2017/05/18/spotify-buys-ai-startup-niland/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Novet |first=Jordan |date=18 May 2017 |title=Spotify just bought an AI startup to help it stay ahead of Apple Music |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/05/18/spotify-buys-niland-french-ai-music-startup.html |access-date=20 May 2017 |website=CNBC |publisher=[[NBCUniversal News Group]] |archive-date=19 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170519064449/http://www.cnbc.com/2017/05/18/spotify-buys-niland-french-ai-music-startup.html |url-status=live }}</ref> In November 2017, Spotify acquired [[Soundtrap]], an online music studio startup.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Perez |first1=Sarah |last2=Lunden |first2=Ingrid |date=17 November 2017 |title=Spotify acquires online music studio Soundtrap as it goes after creators |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/11/17/spotify-acquires-online-music-studio-soundtrap/ |access-date=7 December 2017 |website=TechCrunch |publisher=[[Oath Inc.]] |archive-date=22 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230922085409/https://techcrunch.com/2017/11/17/spotify-acquires-online-music-studio-soundtrap/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Krishna |first=Swapna |date=17 November 2017 |title=Spotify acquires Soundtrap, an online music recording studio |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/11/17/spotify-acquires-soundtrap-music-production-studio/ |access-date=7 December 2017 |website=Engadget |publisher=Oath Inc. |archive-date=8 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208003735/https://www.engadget.com/2017/11/17/spotify-acquires-soundtrap-music-production-studio/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 12 April 2018, Spotify acquired the music licensing platform Loudr.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Perez |first=Sarah |date=12 April 2018 |title=Spotify acquires music licensing platform Loudr |url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/04/12/spotify-acquires-music-licensing-platform-loudr/ |access-date=13 April 2018 |website=techcrunch.com |archive-date=12 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412232711/https://techcrunch.com/2018/04/12/spotify-acquires-music-licensing-platform-loudr/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In August 2018, Spotify bought the exclusive rights to ''[[The Joe Budden Podcast]]'' and expanded the show to a twice-weekly schedule.<ref name="spotify-08-18">{{Cite web |date=22 August 2018 |title='The Joe Budden Podcast' Lands Exclusive Partnership with Spotify |url=https://newsroom.spotify.com/2018-08-22/the-joe-budden-podcast-lands-exclusive-partnership-with-spotify |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604210722/http://newsroom.spotify.com/2018-08-22/the-joe-budden-podcast-lands-exclusive-partnership-with-spotify/ |archive-date=4 June 2019 |access-date=29 June 2019 |website=Spotify Newsroom}}</ref> On 6 February 2019, Spotify acquired the podcast networks [[Gimlet Media]] and Anchor FM Inc., with the goal of establishing themselves as a leading figure in podcasting.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Kafka |first=Peter |date=6 February 2019 |title=Spotify has bought two podcast startups and it wants to buy more |work=Recode |url=https://www.recode.net/2019/2/6/18213456/spotify-podcast-gimlet-anchor-q4-results |access-date=7 February 2019 |archive-date=6 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190206144707/https://www.recode.net/2019/2/6/18213456/spotify-podcast-gimlet-anchor-q4-results |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Warren |first=Tom |date=6 February 2019 |title=Spotify gets serious about podcasts with two acquisitions |work=The Verge |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/2/6/18213462/spotify-podcasts-gimlet-anchor-acquisition |access-date=7 February 2019 |archive-date=7 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207020212/https://www.theverge.com/2019/2/6/18213462/spotify-podcasts-gimlet-anchor-acquisition |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=":5">{{Cite web |last=Russell |first=Jon |date=6 February 2019 |title=Spotify buys Gimlet and Anchor in podcast push, earmarks $500M for more deals |url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/02/06/spotify-doubles-down-on-podcasts/ |access-date=6 February 2019 |website=TechCrunch }}{{Dead link|date=August 2023 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> On 26 March 2019, Spotify announced they would acquire another podcast network, [[Parcast]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=26 March 2019 |title=Spotify acquires another podcast network to keep building its original show catalog |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/3/26/18282301/spotify-podcasts-parcast-acquisition-gimlet-media-anchor |website=The Verge |access-date=27 March 2019 |archive-date=27 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327172436/https://www.theverge.com/2019/3/26/18282301/spotify-podcasts-parcast-acquisition-gimlet-media-anchor |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=26 March 2019 |title=Spotify acquires true crime studio Parcast to expand its original podcast content |url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/03/26/spotify-acquires-true-crime-studio-parcast-to-expand-its-original-podcast-content/ |access-date=2 January 2020 |website=TechCrunch |archive-date=18 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220418200741/https://techcrunch.com/2019/03/26/spotify-acquires-true-crime-studio-parcast-to-expand-its-original-podcast-content/ }}</ref> On 12 September 2019, Spotify acquired SoundBetter, a music production marketplace for people in the music industry to collaborate on projects, and distribute music tracks for licensing.<ref>{{Cite web |date=12 September 2019 |title=Spotify acquires SoundBetter, a music production marketplace, for an undisclosed sum |url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/09/12/spotify-acquires-soundbetter-an-online-marketplace-for-sound-engineers-and-producers/ |access-date=12 September 2019 |website=TechCrunch }}{{Dead link|date=August 2023 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> On 19 November 2019, Spotify announced the acquisition of the exclusive rights to ''[[The Last Podcast on the Left]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |date=19 November 2019 |title='Last Podcast on the Left' Moving Exclusively to Spotify |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/last-podcast-left-moving-exclusively-spotify-1256236 |access-date=20 November 2019 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |language=en |archive-date=20 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191120072845/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/last-podcast-left-moving-exclusively-spotify-1256236 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 5 February 2020, Spotify announced its intent to acquire [[Bill Simmons]]' sports and pop culture blog and podcast network [[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]] for an undisclosed amount. On 19 May 2020, Spotify acquired exclusive rights to stream the popular podcast ''[[The Joe Rogan Experience]]'' beginning in September of that year, under an agreement valued at around US$100 million ({{Inflation|index=US-GDP|value=100000000|start_year=2020|r=-5|fmt=eq}}).<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Robertson |first1=Katie |last2=Scheiber |first2=Noam |date=5 February 2020 |title=Spotify Is Buying The Ringer |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/business/media/spotify-the-ringer-bill-simmons.html |url-status=live |url-access=subscription |access-date=5 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205141009/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/business/media/spotify-the-ringer-bill-simmons.html |archive-date=5 February 2020 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=5 February 2020 |title=Spotify is buying The Ringer to boost its sports podcast content |url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2020/02/05/spotify-is-buying-the-ringer-to-boost-its-sports-podcast-content/ |access-date=5 February 2020 |website=TechCrunch |archive-date=5 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205171110/http://social.techcrunch.com/2020/02/05/spotify-is-buying-the-ringer-to-boost-its-sports-podcast-content/ }}</ref><ref name="Spangler">{{Cite web |last=Spangler |first=Todd |date=19 May 2020 |title=Joe Rogan Will Bring His Podcast Exclusively to Spotify |url=https://variety.com/2020/digital/news/joe-rogan-experience-spotify-podcast-exclusive-1234610885/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200519204108/https://variety.com/2020/digital/news/joe-rogan-experience-spotify-podcast-exclusive-1234610885/ |archive-date=19 May 2020 |access-date=19 May 2020 |website=Variety}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Flegenheimer |first=Matt |date=1 July 2021 |title=Joe Rogan Is Too Big to Cancel |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/07/01/business/joe-rogan.html |url-status=live |url-access=subscription |access-date=29 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210701150506/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/07/01/business/joe-rogan.html |archive-date=1 July 2021 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>''

In November 2020, Spotify announced plans to acquire [[Megaphone (podcasting)|Megaphone]] from [[The Slate Group]] for {{USD|235 million}}.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Carman |first=Ashley |date=10 November 2020 |title=Spotify is acquiring podcast hosting company Megaphone for $235 million |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/11/10/21557458/spotify-megaphone-podcast-streaming-ad-insertion |access-date=10 November 2020 |website=[[The Verge]] |archive-date=10 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201110140132/https://www.theverge.com/2020/11/10/21557458/spotify-megaphone-podcast-streaming-ad-insertion |url-status=live }}</ref> In March 2021, Spotify acquired app developer Betty Labs and their live social audio app, Locker Room,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Fischer |first=Sara |date=31 March 2021 |title=Spotify enters live social audio with acquisition of Locker Room |url=https://www.axios.com/spotify-betty-labs-locker-room-52550d15-3c05-48ed-b924-a9404c31901b.html |access-date=5 April 2021 |website=Axios |language=en |archive-date=1 April 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210401182256/https://www.axios.com/spotify-betty-labs-locker-room-52550d15-3c05-48ed-b924-a9404c31901b.html |url-status=live }}</ref> On 12 May 2021. ''[[Armchair Expert]]'' announced on [[Instagram]] that the podcast would be available exclusively on Spotify beginning 1 July, saying they would continue to maintain the same creative control over the show after the move.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Spangler |first=Todd |date=12 May 2021 |title=Dax Shepard Is Moving His Podcast Exclusively to Spotify This Summer |url=https://variety.com/2021/digital/news/dax-shepard-podcast-spotify-1234971432/ |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=20 December 2022 |archive-date=20 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221220060610/https://variety.com/2021/digital/news/dax-shepard-podcast-spotify-1234971432/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=ArmchairExpPod |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/COyIAl1p4pY/ |url-access=registration |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/iarchive/instagram/armchairexppod/2572153562182683224 |archive-date=25 December 2021 |access-date=14 May 2021 |website=Instagram}}{{cbignore}}</ref> Locker Room was rebranded in June 2021 as [[Spotify Greenroom]], and turned into a [[Clubhouse (app)|Clubhouse]] competitor.<ref>{{Cite web |date=16 June 2021 |title=Spotify launches its live audio app and Clubhouse rival, Spotify Greenroom |url=https://social.techcrunch.com/2021/06/16/spotify-launches-its-live-audio-app-and-clubhouse-rival-spotify-greenroom/ }}{{Dead link|date=July 2023 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The same month, Spotify acquired Podz, a podcast discovery startup.<ref>{{Cite web |date=17 June 2021 |title=Spotify acquires Podz, a podcast discovery platform |url=https://techcrunch.com/2021/06/17/spotify-acquires-podz-a-podcast-discovery-app/ |access-date=18 June 2021 |archive-date=18 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210618221837/https://techcrunch.com/2021/06/17/spotify-acquires-podz-a-podcast-discovery-app/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Also the same month, Spotify bought the exclusive rights to the ''[[Call Her Daddy]]'' podcast.<ref name="auto1">{{Cite web |last=Spangler |first=Todd |date=15 June 2021 |title=Spotify Clinches $60M-Plus Deal With Alex Cooper for 'Call Her Daddy' Podcast, Yanking It Away From Barstool |url=https://variety.com/2021/digital/news/spotify-call-her-daddy-alex-cooper-exclusive-1234996840/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210618153312/https://variety.com/2021/digital/news/spotify-call-her-daddy-alex-cooper-exclusive-1234996840/ |archive-date=18 June 2021 |access-date=18 June 2021 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref> In November 2021, Spotify acquired audiobook company Findaway, including its publishing imprint OrangeSky Audio.<ref>{{Cite web |date=12 November 2021 |title=Spotify Acquires Audiobook Company Findaway |url=https://www.androidheadlines.com/2021/11/spotify-acquires-audiobook-company.html |access-date=21 December 2021 |website=Android Headlines |language=en-US |archive-date=21 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211221021059/https://www.androidheadlines.com/2021/11/spotify-acquires-audiobook-company.html |url-status=live }}</ref> In December 2021, Spotify acquired Whooshkaa, a podcast tech company that develops specialized technology that allows radio broadcasters to easily turn their existing audio content into on-demand podcast programming.<ref>{{Cite web |date=16 December 2021 |title=Spotify acquires podcast tech company Whooshkaa which turns radio broadcasts into on-demand audio |url=https://techcrunch.com/2021/12/16/spotify-acquires-podcast-tech-company-whooshkaa-which-turns-radio-broadcasts-into-on-demand-audio/ |access-date=26 July 2022 |archive-date=26 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220726071125/https://techcrunch.com/2021/12/16/spotify-acquires-podcast-tech-company-whooshkaa-which-turns-radio-broadcasts-into-on-demand-audio/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In February 2022, Spotify acquired Chartable and Podsights. Both are podcast advertising companies.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Carman |first=Ashley |date=16 February 2022 |title=Spotify is acquiring two major podcast tech platforms |url=https://www.theverge.com/2022/2/16/22937826/spotify-podsights-chartable-acquisitions-podcast-marketing-platforms |access-date=22 March 2022 |website=The Verge |language=en |archive-date=22 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220322110803/https://www.theverge.com/2022/2/16/22937826/spotify-podsights-chartable-acquisitions-podcast-marketing-platforms |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2022, Spotify Greenroom rebranded as [[Spotify Greenroom|Spotify Live]],<ref>{{Cite web |date=23 March 2022 |title=Spotify rebranding its live social audio app |url=https://adage.com/article/marketing-news-strategy/spotify-rebranding-its-live-social-audio-app/2407731 |access-date=23 March 2022 |website=Ad Age |language=en |archive-date=23 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220323211644/https://adage.com/article/marketing-news-strategy/spotify-rebranding-its-live-social-audio-app/2407731 |url-status=live }}</ref> which was subsequently planned to be shut down in April 2023.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Chan |first=J. Clara |date=3 April 2023 |title=Spotify Shutters Live Audio App |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/business/business-news/spotify-live-shutters-1235366519/ |magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=4 April 2023 |archive-date=5 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231005000958/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/business/business-news/spotify-live-shutters-1235366519/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In June 2022, Spotify acquired Sonantic, a synthetic voice and video developer.<ref>{{Cite web |date=13 June 2022 |title=Spotify Acquires Synthetic Voice Startup Sonantic |url=https://voicebot.ai/2022/06/13/spotify-acquires-synthetic-voice-startup-sonantic/ |access-date=26 July 2022 |archive-date=26 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220726071715/https://voicebot.ai/2022/06/13/spotify-acquires-synthetic-voice-startup-sonantic/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In July 2022, Spotify acquired [[Heardle]], a [[Wordle]]-inspired music trivia game, for an undisclosed amount;<ref>{{Cite web |date=12 July 2022 |title=Spotify acquired Heardle, the Wordle-like music game |url=https://social.techcrunch.com/2022/07/12/spotify-acquired-heardle-wordle-music-game/ |access-date=15 July 2022 |website=TechCrunch |language=en-US }}{{Dead link|date=August 2023 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Shapiro |first=Ariel |date=12 July 2022 |title=Spotify acquires music trivia game Heardle |url=https://www.theverge.com/2022/7/12/23205078/spotify-heardle-acquisition-music-discovery-wordle-game |access-date=15 July 2022 |website=The Verge |language=en |archive-date=14 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220714201622/https://www.theverge.com/2022/7/12/23205078/spotify-heardle-acquisition-music-discovery-wordle-game |url-status=live }}</ref> Heardle was shut down in May 2023.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Alexander |first=Christina |date=14 April 2023 |title=Farewell Heardle: Spotify Killing Its Version of Wordle Less Than a Year After Acquisition |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/farewell-heardle-spotify-killing-its-version-of-wordle-less-than-a-year-after-acquisition |website=[[IGN]] |access-date=17 April 2023 |archive-date=17 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230417074310/https://www.ign.com/articles/farewell-heardle-spotify-killing-its-version-of-wordle-less-than-a-year-after-acquisition |url-status=live }}</ref> In October 2022, Spotify acquired the [[Dublin]]-based content moderation startup, Kinzen.<ref>{{Cite web |date=6 October 2022 |title=Spotify acquires Dublin-based content moderation startup Kinzen |url=https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/spotify-acquires-dublin-based-content-moderation-startup-kinzen/ |access-date=6 October 2022 |website=Music Business Worldwide |language=en-US |archive-date=6 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221006123341/https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/spotify-acquires-dublin-based-content-moderation-startup-kinzen/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2023, Spotify merged Anchor into their Spotify for Podcasters tool, a rebranding move and to organize its tools for creating, managing, growing, and monetizing their content in one place.<ref name="auto">{{Cite web |last=Perez |first=Sarah |date=2023-03-08 |title=Spotify is revamping its podcaster tools, including Anchor, and is partnering with Patreon |url=https://techcrunch.com/2023/03/08/spotify-is-revamping-its-podcaster-tools-including-anchor-and-is-partnering-with-patreon/ |access-date=2023-03-10 |website=TechCrunch |language=en-US |archive-date=10 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230310122306/https://techcrunch.com/2023/03/08/spotify-is-revamping-its-podcaster-tools-including-anchor-and-is-partnering-with-patreon/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

==== Company partnerships ====
In January 2015, [[Sony]] announced PlayStation Music, a new music service with Spotify as its exclusive partner. PlayStation Music incorporates the Spotify service into Sony's [[PlayStation 3]] and [[PlayStation 4]] gaming consoles, and [[Sony Xperia]] mobile devices. The service launched on 30 March 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lempel |first=Eric |date=30 March 2015 |title=Spotify Launches on PlayStation Music Today |url=http://blog.us.playstation.com/2015/03/30/spotify-launches-on-playstation-music-today/ |access-date=13 November 2016 |publisher=Sony |archive-date=6 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206124233/http://blog.us.playstation.com/2015/03/30/spotify-launches-on-playstation-music-today/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In March 2017, Spotify announced a partnership with the [[South by Southwest]] (SXSW) conference for 2017, presenting specific content in special playlists through an SXSW hub in Spotify's apps. The integration also enabled Spotify within the SXSW GO app to help users discover and explore artists performing at the conference. Two more partnerships were announced in March; one with [[WNYC Studios]], and one with [[Waze]]. The WNYC Studios partnership brought various podcasts from WNYC to Spotify, including ''[[Note to Self]]'', ''[[On the Media]]'' and ''[[Here's the Thing]]''. Spotify also announced that the third season of WNYC Studios' [[2 Dope Queens]] podcast would premiere with a two-week exclusivity period on the service on 21 March 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Rossignol |first=Derrick |date=13 March 2017 |title=Spotify lands '2 Dope Queens' and other hit WNYC podcasts |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/03/13/spotify-lands-2-dope-queens-and-other-hit-wnyc-podcasts/ |access-date=15 March 2017 |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=AOL |archive-date=14 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314114825/https://www.engadget.com/2017/03/13/spotify-lands-2-dope-queens-and-other-hit-wnyc-podcasts/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The Waze partnership allows Waze app users to view directions to destinations within the Spotify app and access their Spotify playlists through the Waze app.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Nieva |first=Richard |date=14 March 2017 |title=Spotify gives you driving directions through Waze |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/spotify-waze-driving-directions-playlist-integrations/ |access-date=15 March 2017 |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |archive-date=14 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314195324/https://www.cnet.com/news/spotify-waze-driving-directions-playlist-integrations/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In October 2017, [[Microsoft]] announced that it would be ending its [[Groove Music]] streaming service by December, with all music from users transferring to Spotify as part of a new partnership.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Warren |first=Tom |date=2 October 2017 |title=Microsoft retires Groove Music service, partners with Spotify |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/10/2/16401898/microsoft-groove-music-pass-discontinued-spotify-partner |access-date=7 December 2017 |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |archive-date=4 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171004225603/https://www.theverge.com/2017/10/2/16401898/microsoft-groove-music-pass-discontinued-spotify-partner |url-status=live }}</ref> In December, Spotify and [[Tencent]]'s music arm, Tencent Music Entertainment (TME), agreed to swap stakes and make an investment in each other's music businesses.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Russell |first=Jon |date=8 December 2017 |title=Spotify and Tencent agree to swap stakes in their music businesses |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/12/08/spotify-tencent-share-swap/ |access-date=8 December 2017 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[Oath Inc.]] |archive-date=9 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171209025013/https://techcrunch.com/2017/12/08/spotify-tencent-share-swap/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Sawers |first=Paul |date=8 December 2017 |title=Spotify and China's Tencent invest in each other as part of 'strategic collaboration' |url=https://venturebeat.com/2017/12/08/spotify-and-chinas-tencent-invest-in-each-other-as-part-of-strategic-collaboration/ |access-date=8 December 2017 |website=[[VentureBeat]] |archive-date=9 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171209032410/https://venturebeat.com/2017/12/08/spotify-and-chinas-tencent-invest-in-each-other-as-part-of-strategic-collaboration/ |url-status=live }}</ref> As a result of this transaction, Spotify gained a 9% stake in TME with TME gaining a 7.5% stake in Spotify.<ref>{{Cite web |date=March 2018 |title=Tencent Music, Spotify's strategic partner in China, is valued at over $12B – TechCrunch |url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/02/28/tencent-music-spotify/ |access-date=3 June 2018 |website=techcrunch.com |archive-date=8 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608205720/https://techcrunch.com/2018/02/28/tencent-music-spotify/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In February 2018, Spotify integrated with the gaming-oriented voice chat service [[Discord (software)|Discord]] on desktop clients, allowing users to display their currently playing song as a rich presence on their profile, and invite other users with Spotify Premium to group "listening parties".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Farokhmanesh |first=Megan |date=1 February 2018 |title=Please tell me Spotify's new partnership with Discord will fix its bad gamer playlists |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/1/16950076/discord-spotify-partnership-streaming-playlists-gaming-listening-habits |access-date=5 February 2020 |website=The Verge |archive-date=5 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205171913/https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/1/16950076/discord-spotify-partnership-streaming-playlists-gaming-listening-habits |url-status=live }}</ref> In April, Spotify announced a discounted entertainment bundle with video-on-demand provider [[Hulu]], which included discounted rates for university students.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Perez |first=Sarah |date=11 April 2018 |title=Spotify and Hulu launch a discounted entertainment bundle for $12.99 per month |url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/04/11/spotify-and-hulu-launch-a-discounted-entertainment-bundle-for-12-99-per-month/ |access-date=11 April 2018 |website=TechCrunch |archive-date=11 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180411135224/https://techcrunch.com/2018/04/11/spotify-and-hulu-launch-a-discounted-entertainment-bundle-for-12-99-per-month/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In May 2020, Spotify teamed up with [[ESPN]] and [[Netflix]] to curate podcasts around their [[Michael Jordan]] documentary ''[[The Last Dance (miniseries)|The Last Dance]]'',<ref>{{Cite web |last=Carman |first=Ashley |date=1 May 2020 |title=Netflix and ESPN team up with Spotify to curate podcasts around their Michael Jordan documentary |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/5/1/21243927/netflix-espn-spotify-the-last-dance-michael-jordan-documentary-podcast |access-date=3 May 2020 |website=The Verge |archive-date=3 May 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200503061820/https://www.theverge.com/2020/5/1/21243927/netflix-espn-spotify-the-last-dance-michael-jordan-documentary-podcast |url-status=live }}</ref> and in September, Spotify signed a deal with [[Chernin Entertainment]] to produce movies and TV shows.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Spotify Strikes First-Look Deal To Adapt Podcasts As Movies And TV Shows |url=https://comicbook.com/movies/news/spotify-strikes-first-look-deal-adapt-podcasts-movies-and-tv/ |access-date=25 September 2020 |website=Movies |archive-date=26 September 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200926164245/https://comicbook.com/movies/news/spotify-strikes-first-look-deal-adapt-podcasts-movies-and-tv/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 2020 and 2021, Spotify and [[DC Comics|DC]], a brand at the time under [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Entertainment]] signed deals to create audio shows on the platform around characters such as Catwoman, Wonder Woman, the Riddler, Batgirl, Superman and Lois Lane, among others.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Alexander |first=Julia |date=2021-02-22 |title=DC Comics is launching a podcast universe on Spotify |url=https://www.theverge.com/2021/2/22/22295156/dc-comics-spotify-universe-podcast-superhero |access-date=2023-03-10 |website=The Verge |language=en-US |archive-date=10 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230310122306/https://www.theverge.com/2021/2/22/22295156/dc-comics-spotify-universe-podcast-superhero |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Chan |first=J. Clara |date=2023-03-08 |title=Behind Spotify's Growing DC Comics Audioverse |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/business/digital/spotify-dc-comics-harley-quinn-joker-1235343386/ |access-date=2023-03-10 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |language=en-US |archive-date=10 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230310122307/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/business/digital/spotify-dc-comics-harley-quinn-joker-1235343386/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 2022, Spotify became the official streaming partner of [[FC Barcelona]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Cohen |first=David |date=15 March 2022 |title=Spotify to Become Main Partner, Official Audio Streaming Partner of FC Barcelona |url=https://www.adweek.com/social-marketing/spotify-to-become-main-partner-official-audio-streaming-partner-of-fc-barcelona/ |access-date=23 March 2022 |language=en-US |archive-date=26 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220326131041/https://www.adweek.com/social-marketing/spotify-to-become-main-partner-official-audio-streaming-partner-of-fc-barcelona/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In May 2022, Spotify announced a partnership with the online game platform and game creation system the [[Roblox Corporation]], the partnership saw Spotify as the first streaming brand to have a presence within the game with the launch of "Spotify Island".<ref>{{Cite journal |date=3 May 2022 |title=Spotify becomes first music streamer to launch on Roblox |url=https://techcrunch.com/2022/05/03/spotify-becomes-first-music-streamer-to-launch-on-roblox/ |journal=Tech Crunch |access-date=3 May 2022 |archive-date=3 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220503110555/https://techcrunch.com/2022/05/03/spotify-becomes-first-music-streamer-to-launch-on-roblox/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In March 2023, Spotify announced a partnership with [[Patreon]], which Spotify claimed would "enable creators to expand their creative business through direct payments from fans, and allow fans to listen to their Patreon content on Spotify".<ref name="auto"/><ref>{{Cite web |last=Makari |first=Reem |date=8 March 2023 |title=Spotify unveils Patreon partnership, redesigned app and more |url=https://www.podpod.com/article/1815813 |access-date=2023-07-01 |website=www.podpod.com |language=en |archive-date=5 March 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240305105128/https://www.podpod.com/article/1815813/spotify-unveils-patreon-partnership-redesigned-app |url-status=live }}</ref>

==== Dispute with Apple ====
In July 2015, Spotify launched an email campaign to urge its [[App Store (iOS)|App Store]] subscribers to cancel their subscriptions and start new ones through its website, bypassing the 30% transaction fee for in-app purchases required for [[iOS]] applications by technology company [[Apple Inc.]]<ref>{{Cite web |last=Welch |first=Chris |date=8 July 2015 |title=Spotify urges iPhone customers to stop paying through Apple's App Store |url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/7/8/8913105/spotify-apple-app-store-email |access-date=11 December 2017 |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |archive-date=28 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190928030015/https://www.theverge.com/2015/7/8/8913105/spotify-apple-app-store-email |url-status=live}}</ref> A later update to the Spotify app on iOS was rejected by Apple, prompting Spotify's general counsel Horacio Gutierrez to write a letter to Apple's then-general counsel Bruce Sewell, stating: "This latest episode raises serious concerns under both U.S. and EU competition law. It continues a troubling pattern of behavior by Apple to exclude and diminish the competitiveness of Spotify on iOS and as a rival to [[Apple Music]], particularly when seen against the backdrop of Apple's previous anticompetitive conduct aimed at Spotify ... we cannot stand by as Apple uses the App Store approval process as a weapon to harm competitors."<ref>{{Cite web |last=Kafka |first=Peter |date=30 June 2016 |title=Spotify says Apple won't approve a new version of its app because it doesn't want competition for Apple Music |url=http://www.recode.net/2016/6/30/12067578/spotify-apple-app-store-rejection |access-date=22 January 2017 |website=[[Recode]] |archive-date=30 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430063409/https://www.recode.net/2016/6/30/12067578/spotify-apple-app-store-rejection |url-status=live}}</ref>

Sewell responded to the letter: "We find it troubling that you are asking for exemptions to the rules we apply to all developers and are publicly resorting to rumors and half-truths about our service." He also elaborated that "Our guidelines apply equally to all app developers, whether they are game developers, e-book sellers, video-streaming services or digital music distributors; and regardless of whether they compete against Apple. We did not alter our behavior or our rules when we introduced our own music streaming service or when Spotify became a competitor". Furthermore, he stated that "There is nothing in Apple's conduct that 'amounts to a violation of applicable antitrust laws.' Far from it. ... I would be happy to facilitate an expeditious review and approval of your app as soon as you provide us with something that is compliant with the App Store's rules".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Paczkowski |first=John |date=1 July 2016 |title=Apple Slams Spotify For Asking For "Preferential Treatment" |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/johnpaczkowski/apple-fires-back-at-spotify-for-asking-for-preferential-trea |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701215735/https://www.buzzfeed.com/johnpaczkowski/apple-fires-back-at-spotify-for-asking-for-preferential-trea |archive-date=1 July 2016 |access-date=11 December 2017 |website=[[BuzzFeed]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Raymundo |first=Oscar |date=1 July 2016 |title=Apple slams Spotify for criticizing the App Store as anti-competitive |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/3090219/ios/spotify-lawyers-up-against-apple-for-rejecting-its-updated-ios-app.html |access-date=11 December 2017 |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |archive-date=12 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212031529/https://www.macworld.com/article/3090219/ios/spotify-lawyers-up-against-apple-for-rejecting-its-updated-ios-app.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

In the following months, Spotify joined several other companies in filing a letter with the [[European Union]]'s [[antitrust]] body indirectly accusing Apple and [[Google]] of "abusing their 'privileged position' at the top of the market", by referring to "some" companies as having "transformed into 'gatekeepers' rather than 'gateways'".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Campbell |first=Mikey |date=5 May 2017 |title=Spotify, others file EU complaint over Apple and Google app store practices |url=http://appleinsider.com/articles/17/05/05/spotify-others-file-eu-complaint-over-apple-and-google-app-store-practices |access-date=6 May 2017 |website=AppleInsider |archive-date=6 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170506053524/http://appleinsider.com/articles/17/05/05/spotify-others-file-eu-complaint-over-apple-and-google-app-store-practices |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Miller |first=Chance |date=6 May 2017 |title=Spotify again accuses Apple of abusing its size & acting as a 'gatekeeper' |url=https://9to5mac.com/2017/05/06/spotify-again-accuses-apple-of-abusing-its-size-acting-as-a-gatekeeper/ |access-date=6 May 2017 |website=9to5Mac |archive-date=14 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914125940/https://9to5mac.com/2017/05/06/spotify-again-accuses-apple-of-abusing-its-size-acting-as-a-gatekeeper/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The complaint led to the European Union announcing that it would prepare an initiative by the end of 2017 for a possible law addressing unfair competition practices.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Fioretti |first=Julia |date=10 May 2017 |title=EU to tackle complaints over tech companies' trading practices |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-eu-digital-idUSKBN18614K |access-date=10 May 2017 |website=Reuters |publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]] |archive-date=10 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510102415/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-eu-digital-idUSKBN18614K |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Lovejoy |first=Ben |date=10 May 2017 |title=EU planning a new law addressing 'unfair contractual clauses' following Spotify's complaint against Apple |url=https://9to5mac.com/2017/05/10/eu-apple-spotify-complaint/ |access-date=10 May 2017 |website=9to5Mac |archive-date=16 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516215828/https://9to5mac.com/2017/05/10/eu-apple-spotify-complaint/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Spotify released the first version of its [[Apple Watch]] app in November 2018, allowing playback control of the iPhone via the watch. Users can also choose which devices to play music on via Bluetooth.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Spotify officially releases the first version of its Apple Watch app |work=Ars Technica |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2018/11/spotify-officially-releases-first-version-of-its-apple-watch-app/ |access-date=14 November 2018 |archive-date=23 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423014248/https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2018/11/spotify-officially-releases-first-version-of-its-apple-watch-app/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In a further escalation of the dispute with Apple, on 13 March 2019, Spotify filed an antitrust complaint with the European Commission over unfair app store practices. Two days later, Apple responded, stating that the claim was misleading rhetoric and that Spotify wanted benefits of a free app without being a free app. Spotify responded with a statement calling Apple a monopolist and stated that they had only filed the complaint as Apple's actions hurt competition and consumers and clearly violated the law. It also said that Apple believed Spotify users on the app store were Apple's customers and not Spotify's.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Rossignol |first=Joe |title=Spotify on Apple's Response to App Store Dispute: 'Every Monopolist Will Suggest They Have Done Nothing Wrong' |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2019/03/16/spotify-calls-apple-monopolist/ |access-date=19 March 2019 |website=www.macrumors.com |date=16 March 2019 |archive-date=27 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727111459/https://www.macrumors.com/2019/03/16/spotify-calls-apple-monopolist/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Apple responded to Spotify's claims by counter-claiming that Spotify's market reach and user base would not have been possible without the Apple App Store platform. Additionally, Apple stated that they have attempted to work with Spotify to integrate the service better with Apple's products, such as [[Siri]] and Apple Watch.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Addressing Spotify's Claims |url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2019/03/addressing-spotifys-claims/ |access-date=20 November 2019 |website=Apple Newsroom |archive-date=6 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190606021032/https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2019/03/addressing-spotifys-claims/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2019, under [[iOS 13]], it became possible to play Spotify music using Siri commands.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Meek |first=Andy |date=7 October 2019 |title=Apple just finally added Spotify integration to Siri in iOS 13 |url=https://bgr.com/2019/10/07/apple-vs-spotify-siri-integration-ios-13/ |access-date=8 October 2019 |website=BGR |archive-date=7 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191007212141/https://bgr.com/2019/10/07/apple-vs-spotify-siri-integration-ios-13/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Spotify was one of the first companies to support [[Epic Games]] in their [[Epic Games v. Apple|lawsuit against Apple]], which was filed after Epic also tried to bypass Apple's 30% fee for [[microtransactions]] in [[Fortnite]]. In September 2020, Spotify, Epic, and other companies founded [[The Coalition for App Fairness]], which aims for better conditions for the inclusion of apps in [[app store]]s.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Amadeo |first=Ron |date=24 September 2020 |title=Epic, Spotify, and others take on Apple with "Coalition for App Fairness" |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2020/09/epic-spotify-and-others-take-on-apple-with-coalition-for-app-fairness/ |access-date=26 September 2020 |website=Ars Technica |archive-date=24 September 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200924195429/https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2020/09/epic-spotify-and-others-take-on-apple-with-coalition-for-app-fairness/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

==== Dispute with Kakao Entertainment Corp. ====
On 1 March 2021, Spotify confirmed that its platform would no longer have access to music from artists represented by [[Kakao Entertainment]]. However, after talking it out and renewing the contracts between the two, Spotify later announced that they had reached an agreement with Kakao Entertainment, allowing their content to be available once again on the platform across the globe.<ref>{{Cite web |date=10 March 2021 |title=Spotify and K-Pop Label Kakao Settle Licensing Dispute, Music Returning to Platform |url=https://variety.com/2021/digital/news/spotify-k-pop-kakao-licensing-dispute-1234927727/ |access-date=15 February 2022 |archive-date=15 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220215025336/https://variety.com/2021/digital/news/spotify-k-pop-kakao-licensing-dispute-1234927727/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

==== Functionality ====
In November 2021, Spotify hid the "shuffle" button for albums following a request by singer [[Adele]], arguing that tracks in albums are supposed to be played back in the order specified by the artist in order to "tell a story".<ref>{{Cite web |date=21 November 2021 |title=Spotify hides shuffle button after Adele says albums should 'tell a story' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2021/nov/21/spotify-hides-shuffle-button-adele-albums-should-tell-a-story |access-date=19 April 2022 |website=The Guardian |language=en |archive-date=19 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220419010842/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2021/nov/21/spotify-hides-shuffle-button-adele-albums-should-tell-a-story |url-status=live }}</ref>

==== NFTs ====
In May 2022, Spotify began testing a feature that would allow select artists to promote their [[Non-fungible token|NFTs]] via their profiles. Some artists included in this initial test phase were [[Steve Aoki]] and [[the Wombats]]. The testing was very limited in nature and was only available on Spotify's Android app in the US.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Exclusive: Spotify tests letting artists promote NFTs on their profiles – Music Ally |date=13 May 2022 |url=https://musically.com/2022/05/13/spotify-artists-promote-nfts/ |access-date=17 May 2022 |archive-date=17 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220517000910/https://musically.com/2022/05/13/spotify-artists-promote-nfts/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

==== Artificial streams ====
In May 2023, Spotify removed tens of thousands of songs, roughly 7% of the tracks uploaded by the Boomy, due to suspected “artificial streaming”, the practice of using online bots to inflate the listening statistics.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Nicolaou |first1=Anna |title=Spotify ejects thousands of AI-made songs in purge of fake streams |url=https://www.ft.com/content/b6802c8f-50e7-4df8-8682-cca794881e30 |access-date=2024-01-20 |website=www.ft.com |archive-date=21 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240121235230/https://www.ft.com/content/b6802c8f-50e7-4df8-8682-cca794881e30 |url-status=live }}</ref>

== Business model ==
[[File:Spotify HK Stockholm.jpg|thumb|Spotify offices in Stockholm, 2024]]
Spotify operates under a [[freemium]] business model (basic services are free, while additional features are offered via paid subscriptions). Spotify generates revenue by selling premium streaming subscriptions to users and advertising placements to third parties. Some of the premium options users may choose from include individual, duo, family, and student.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Spotify Premium |url=http://www.spotify.com/us/premium/ |access-date=14 February 2022 |website=Spotify |language=en-US |archive-date=13 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220213121532/https://www.spotify.com/us/premium/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In December 2013, the company launched a new website, "Spotify for Artists", explaining its business model and revenue data. Spotify gets its content from major record labels as well as [[independent artist]]s and pays [[copyright]] holders [[royalties]] for streaming music. The company pays 70% of its total revenue to rights holders. Spotify for Artists states that the company does not have a fixed per-play rate; instead, it considers factors such as the user's home country and the individual artist's royalty rate. Rights holders received an average per-play payout between $.000029 and $.0084.<ref name="Spotify business">{{Cite web |title=How is Spotify contributing to the music business? |url=http://www.spotifyartists.com/spotify-explained/ |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20141103193456/http://www.spotifyartists.com/spotify-explained/ |archive-date=3 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2016 |publisher=Spotify}}</ref>

In 2013, Spotify revealed that it paid artists an average of $0.007 per stream. ''[[Music Week]]'' editor Tim Ingham commented that while the figure may "initially seem alarming," he noted: "Unlike buying a CD or download, streaming is not a one-off payment. Hundreds of millions of streams of tracks are happening every day, which quickly multiplies the potential revenues on offer – and is a constant long-term source of income for artists."<ref>{{Cite web |date=4 December 2013 |title=Spotify reveals artists earn $0.007 per stream |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-25217353 |access-date=22 January 2017 |website=BBC News |publisher=BBC |archive-date=6 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206123918/http://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-25217353 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to [[Ben Sisario]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'', approximately 13,000 out of seven million artists (0.19%) on Spotify generated $50,000 ({{Inflation|index=US-GDP|value=50000|start_year=2020|r=-1|fmt=eq}}) or more in payments in 2020.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ovide |first=Shira |date=22 March 2021 |title=Streaming Saved Music. Artists Hate It. |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/03/22/technology/streaming-music-economics.html |url-access=limited |access-date=26 March 2021 |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20211228/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/03/22/technology/streaming-music-economics.html |archive-date=28 December 2021 |issn=0362-4331}}{{cbignore}}</ref>

In November 2023, Spotify announced a new royalty model taking effect in 2024, aiming to reduce the amount of "fraudulent" royalties collected from "functional" non-music tracks with short lengths (such as environmental sounds and [[white noise]]). Under the model, tracks must reach at least 1,000 listens in 12 months to become eligible for royalties, "functional" tracks will require a longer amount of play time to count as a listen, and distributors will face reprimands if their content is responsible for generating "fradulant" royalties. The changes faced a mixed reaction from the music industry, who believed that it would be detrimental to emerging musicians, but would make a larger share of total royalty payments available to musicians.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Aswad |first=Jem |date=2023-11-06 |title=What Spotify's New Royalty Model Really Means |url=https://variety.com/2023/music/news/spotify-new-royalty-model-really-means-1235781554/ |access-date=2023-12-15 |website=Variety |language=en-US |archive-date=15 December 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231215033131/https://variety.com/2023/music/news/spotify-new-royalty-model-really-means-1235781554/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-11-02 |title=Spotify's New Royalty Model Explained by an Expert |url=https://consequence.net/2023/11/spotify-royalty-model-op-ed/ |access-date=2023-12-15 |website=Consequence of Sound |language=en-US |archive-date=15 December 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231215033131/https://consequence.net/2023/11/spotify-royalty-model-op-ed/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-11-05 |title=Confirmed: From 2024, tracks on Spotify will have to be played 1,000 times before they start earning money |url=https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/confirmed-next-year-tracks-on-spotify-1000-plays/ |access-date=2023-12-15 |website=Music Business Worldwide |language=en-US |archive-date=15 December 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231215033131/https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/confirmed-next-year-tracks-on-spotify-1000-plays/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

