None of these subscriptions limit listening time.

In March 2014, Spotify introduced a discounted Premium subscription tier for students in which students in the United States enrolled in a university pay half-price for a Premium subscription.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Hernandez |first=Brian Anthony |date=25 March 2014 |title=Spotify Slashes Subscription Prices for College Students |url=http://mashable.com/2014/03/25/spotify-premium-student-discount/ |access-date=2 June 2017 |website=[[Mashable]] |archive-date=3 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170503095714/http://mashable.com/2014/03/25/spotify-premium-student-discount/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In April 2017, the discount was expanded to 33 more countries.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Dalton |first=Andrew |date=19 April 2017 |title=Spotify's half-price plan for students comes to 33 more countries |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/04/19/spotifys-half-price-premium-for-students-33-more-countries/ |access-date=19 April 2017 |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=[[Oath Inc.]] |archive-date=19 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419083346/https://www.engadget.com/2017/04/19/spotifys-half-price-premium-for-students-33-more-countries/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Lancaster |first=Luke |date=19 April 2017 |title=Students can now pick up Spotify Premium for half price |url=https://www.cnet.com/au/news/students-can-now-pick-up-spotify-premium-for-half-price/ |access-date=19 April 2017 |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |archive-date=19 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419200653/https://www.cnet.com/au/news/students-can-now-pick-up-spotify-premium-for-half-price/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Spotify introduced a Family subscription in October 2014, which allows up to 5 family members to have a premium subscription.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Warren |first=Tom |date=20 October 2014 |title=Spotify Family lets you share a subscription from $14.99 per month |url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/10/20/7013227/spotify-family-shared-premium-subscription-pricing-features |access-date=2 June 2017 |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |archive-date=20 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920093155/https://www.theverge.com/2014/10/20/7013227/spotify-family-shared-premium-subscription-pricing-features |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=O'Hear |first=Steve |date=20 October 2014 |title=Spotify Introduces Family Plan, Starting At $14.99 Per Month For Two Members |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/10/20/spotify-introduces-family-plan-starting-at-14-99-per-month-for-two-members/ |access-date=2 June 2017 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=Oath Inc. |archive-date=20 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920093427/https://techcrunch.com/2014/10/20/spotify-introduces-family-plan-starting-at-14-99-per-month-for-two-members/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In May 2016, the limit was changed to 6 family members, and the price was reduced.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Dillet |first=Romain |date=23 May 2016 |title=Spotify family plan is now cheaper, $14.99 for up to 6 people |url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/05/23/spotify-family-plan-is-now-cheaper-14-99-for-up-to-6-people/ |access-date=2 June 2017 |website=TechCrunch |publisher=Oath Inc. |archive-date=20 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920093429/https://techcrunch.com/2016/05/23/spotify-family-plan-is-now-cheaper-14-99-for-up-to-6-people/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The Family subscription provides access to [[Spotify Kids]].<ref name=":12">{{Cite web |last=Johnson |first=Dave |date=24 November 2021 |title=How to sign up for Spotify's Family plan, the streaming service's membership for up to 6 people |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/spotify-family-plan |access-date=1 December 2021 |website=[[Business Insider]] |language=en-US |archive-date=1 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211201035110/https://www.businessinsider.com/spotify-family-plan |url-status=live }}</ref>

In November 2018, Spotify announced it was opening up Spotify Connect to all of the users using its Free service, however, these changes still required products supporting Spotify Connect to support the latest [[software development kit]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Heater |first=Brian |date=7 November 2018 |title=Spotify Connect speakers will soon work with its free tier |url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/11/07/spotify-connect-speakers-will-soon-work-with-its-free-tier/ |access-date=10 November 2018 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=Oath Inc. |archive-date=9 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181109151337/https://techcrunch.com/2018/11/07/spotify-connect-speakers-will-soon-work-with-its-free-tier/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Sawers |first=Paul |date=7 November 2018 |title=Spotify Connect for speakers opens to free users via a new SDK |url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/11/07/spotify-connect-opens-to-free-users-via-a-new-sdk-for-hardware-makers/ |access-date=10 November 2018 |website=[[Venturebeat]] |archive-date=10 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181110120453/https://venturebeat.com/2018/11/07/spotify-connect-opens-to-free-users-via-a-new-sdk-for-hardware-makers/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In July 2020,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Guinness |first=Harry |title=What Is Spotify Duo, and Is It Right for You? |url=https://www.howtogeek.com/680795/what-is-spotify-duo-and-is-it-right-for-you/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220706191004/https://www.howtogeek.com/680795/what-is-spotify-duo-and-is-it-right-for-you/ |archive-date=6 July 2022 |access-date=6 July 2022 |website=How-To Geek |date=8 July 2020 |language=en-US}}</ref> Spotify added another tier, Premium Duo.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Spotify Premium Duo |url=http://www.spotify.com/uk/duo/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220706191353/https://www.spotify.com/uk/duo/ |archive-date=6 July 2022 |access-date=6 July 2022 |website=Spotify |language=en-GB}}</ref> This is aimed at couples and for $12.99 it lets up to 2 people (living at the same address) share a subscription.

In February 2021, Spotify announced their plans to introduce a HiFi subscription, to offer listening in [[high fidelity]], lossless sound quality. The rollout for the HiFi tier is yet to be announced.<ref name=":3">{{Cite web |date=22 February 2021 |title=Spotify HiFi subscription to launch in select markets later this year |url=https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/spotify-hifi-subscription-to-launch-in-select-markets-later-this-year/ |access-date=22 February 2021 |website=[[Music Business Worldwide]] |archive-date=22 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210222171632/https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/spotify-hifi-subscription-to-launch-in-select-markets-later-this-year/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In August 2021, Spotify launched a test subscription tier called Spotify Plus. The subscription costs $0.99 and is supposed to be a combination of the free and premium tiers. Subscribers to this plan will still receive ads but will get the ability to listen to songs without shuffle mode and skip any number of tracks. The company reported that the tier conditions may change before its full launch.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Porter |first=Jon |date=3 August 2021 |title=Spotify is testing a less restrictive ad-supported tier costing $0.99 a month |url=https://www.theverge.com/2021/8/3/22607203/spotify-plus-ad-supported-tier-unlimited-skips-on-demand-listening |access-date=3 August 2021 |website=The Verge |archive-date=3 August 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210803083215/https://www.theverge.com/2021/8/3/22607203/spotify-plus-ad-supported-tier-unlimited-skips-on-demand-listening |url-status=live }}</ref> This might have been discontinued (at least in some regions) according to an email sent to a redditor.<ref>{{Cite web |date=9 February 2022 |title=Spotify is ending its Spotify Plus service. I hope that it just becomes the default free service now, otherwise I'm really going to miss on demand music streaming for $3 a month |url=https://www.reddit.com/r/truespotify/comments/sopj5h/spotify_is_ending_its_spotify_plus_service_i_hope/ |website=Reddit |access-date=6 July 2022 |archive-date=6 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220706193922/https://www.reddit.com/r/truespotify/comments/sopj5h/spotify_is_ending_its_spotify_plus_service_i_hope/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Monetization ===
In 2008, just after launch, the company made a loss of 31.8 million Swedish kronor (US$4.4 million).<ref>{{Cite web |last=Nylander |first=Johan |date=17 August 2009 |title=Spotify doubled its loss last year |url=http://www.swedishwire.com/business/751-spotify-doubled-its-loss-last-year |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303181238/http://www.swedishwire.com/business/751-spotify-doubled-its-loss-last-year |archive-date=3 March 2016 |access-date=7 November 2016 |website=The Swedish Wire}}</ref> In October 2010, ''[[Wired (website)|Wired]]'' reported that Spotify was making more money for labels in Sweden than any other retailer "online or off".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Geere |first=Duncan |date=29 October 2010 |title=Spotify now top-tier music revenue source in Sweden |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2010-10/29/spotify-swedish-revenue |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101030230717/http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2010-10/29/spotify-swedish-revenue |archive-date=30 October 2010 |access-date=22 January 2017 |website=[[Wired (website)|Wired]]}}</ref> Years after growth and expansion, a November 2012 report suggested strong momentum for the company. In 2011, it reported a near US$60 million net loss from revenue of $244 million ({{Inflation|index=US-GDP|value=244000000|start_year=2011|r=-5|fmt=eq}}), while it was expected to generate a net loss of $40 million ({{Inflation|index=US-GDP|value=40000000|start_year=2012|r=-4|fmt=eq}}) from revenue of $500 million in 2012 ({{Inflation|index=US-GDP|value=500000000|start_year=2012|r=-5|fmt=eq}}).<ref>{{Cite web |last=Eldon |first=Eric |date=10 November 2012 |title=Spotify Is Having A Good 2012: Revenues Could Reach $500M As It Expands The Digital Music Market |url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/11/10/spotify-is-having-a-good-2012-revenues-could-reach-500m-as-it-expands-the-digital-music-market/ |access-date=22 January 2017 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |archive-date=2 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402075109/https://techcrunch.com/2012/11/10/spotify-is-having-a-good-2012-revenues-could-reach-500m-as-it-expands-the-digital-music-market/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Another source of income was music purchases from within the app, however this service was removed in January 2013.<ref name="No purchase">{{Cite web |last=Brian |first=Matt |date=4 January 2013 |title=Spotify is no longer offering new music download purchases to its users |url=https://thenextweb.com/media/2013/01/04/spotify-is-no-longer-offering-new-music-download-purchases-to-its-users/ |access-date=22 January 2017 |website=The Next Web |archive-date=13 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413203243/https://thenextweb.com/media/2013/01/04/spotify-is-no-longer-offering-new-music-download-purchases-to-its-users/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In May 2016, Spotify announced "Sponsored Playlists", a monetisation opportunity in which brands can specify the audiences they have in mind, with Spotify matching the marketer with suitable music in a playlist.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Swant |first=Marty |date=26 May 2016 |title=Spotify Will Now Let Brands Sponsor the Most Popular Playlists |url=http://www.adweek.com/digital/spotify-will-now-let-brands-sponsor-most-popular-playlists-171706/ |access-date=20 June 2017 |website=[[Adweek]] |publisher=Beringer Capital |archive-date=15 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170615101820/http://www.adweek.com/digital/spotify-will-now-let-brands-sponsor-most-popular-playlists-171706/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Morrison |first=Maureen |date=26 May 2016 |title=Spotify Opens Its Popular Playlists to Sponsors |url=http://adage.com/article/digital/spotify-expands-ad-formats-sponsored-playlists/304174/ |access-date=20 June 2017 |website=[[Advertising Age]] |archive-date=12 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170612151816/http://adage.com/article/digital/spotify-expands-ad-formats-sponsored-playlists/304174/ |url-status=live }}</ref> That September, Spotify announced that it had paid a total of over $5 billion to the music industry. In June 2017, as part of renegotiated licenses with Universal Music Group and Merlin Network, Spotify's financial filings revealed its agreement to pay more than $2 billion ({{Inflation|index=US-GDP|value=2000000000|start_year=2017|r=-6|fmt=eq}}) in minimum payments over the next two years.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ingham |first=Tim |date=29 September 2016 |title=Spotify has already paid the music industry over $1.2bn this year |work=Music Business Worldwide |url=https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/spotify-has-already-paid-the-music-business-1-2bn-this-year/ |access-date=28 May 2017 |archive-date=12 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190612092424/https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/spotify-has-already-paid-the-music-business-1-2bn-this-year/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Kafka |first=Peter |date=15 June 2017 |title=Spotify has guaranteed to pay big music labels billions over the next two years |url=https://www.recode.net/2017/6/15/15807382/spotify-revenue-2016-financials-guarantee-payment-universal-merlin |access-date=22 June 2017 |website=[[Recode]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |archive-date=17 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170617112816/https://www.recode.net/2017/6/15/15807382/spotify-revenue-2016-financials-guarantee-payment-universal-merlin |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last1=Turner |first1=Giles |last2=Shaw |first2=Lucas |date=15 June 2017 |title=Spotify's Loss More Than Doubles Even as User Growth Surges |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-06-15/spotify-losses-widen-after-music-site-flags-accounting-errors |access-date=22 June 2017 |website=Bloomberg Technology |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |archive-date=22 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422164310/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-06-15/spotify-losses-widen-after-music-site-flags-accounting-errors |url-status=live }}</ref>

{{As of|2017}}, Spotify was not yet a profitable company.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Plummer |first=Robert |date=12 February 2017 |title=The clock is ticking for Spotify |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-38930699 |access-date=12 February 2017 |website=BBC News |publisher=BBC |archive-date=12 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170212032459/http://www.bbc.com/news/business-38930699 |url-status=live }}</ref> Spotify's revenue for Q1 2020 amounted to €1.85 billion ($2 billion). A large part of this sum, €1.7 billion ($1.84 billion), came from Spotify Premium subscribers. Gross profit in the same quarter amounted to €472 million ($511 million), with an operating loss of €17 million ($18 million).<ref>{{Cite web |date=20 December 2018 |title=Spotify Usage and Revenue Statistics (2020) |url=https://www.businessofapps.com/data/spotify-statistics/ |access-date=14 May 2020 |website=Business of Apps |archive-date=3 June 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200603125727/https://www.businessofapps.com/data/spotify-statistics/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Despite subscriber and podcasts growth, during Q2 of 2020, Spotify reported a loss of €356 million (€1.91 per share). The "deeper" loss came as a result of the company's tax debt to over one-third of its employees in Sweden.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Steele |first=Anne |date=29 July 2020 |title=Spotify Loss Deepens Despite Subscriber, Podcast Growth |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/spotify-loss-deepens-despite-subscriber-podcast-growth-11596016801?mod=business_lead_pos6 |access-date=29 July 2020 |archive-date=29 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200729212758/https://www.wsj.com/articles/spotify-loss-deepens-despite-subscriber-podcast-growth-11596016801?mod=business_lead_pos6 |url-status=live }}</ref>

==== Funding ====
In February 2010, Spotify received a small investment from [[Founders Fund]], where board member [[Sean Parker]] was recruited to assist Spotify in "winning the labels over in the world's largest music market". In June 2011, Spotify secured $100 million of funding ({{Inflation|index=US-GDP|value=100000000|start_year=2011|r=-5|fmt=eq}}) and planned to use this to support its US launch.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Bradshaw |first1=Tim |last2=Menn |first2=Joseph |date=1 March 2010 |title=Spotify-MOG battle heats up |url=https://www.ft.com/content/7a289b4e-249b-11df-8be0-00144feab49a |access-date=22 January 2017 |website=[[Financial Times]] |publisher=[[The Nikkei]] |archive-date=6 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206124041/https://www.ft.com/content/7a289b4e-249b-11df-8be0-00144feab49a |url-status=live }}</ref> The new round of funding valued the company at $1 billion.<ref>{{Cite web |date=18 June 2011 |title=Spotify valued at $1bn, coming to US |url=http://www.investoo.co.uk/spotify-valued-at-1bn-coming-to-us/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325031236/http://www.investoo.co.uk/spotify-valued-at-1bn-coming-to-us/ |archive-date=25 March 2012 |access-date=7 November 2016 |website=Investoo}}</ref> A [[Goldman Sachs]]-led round of funding closed in November 2012, raising around $100 million ({{Inflation|index=US-GDP|value=100000000|start_year=2012|r=-5|fmt=eq}}) at a $3 billion valuation ({{Inflation|index=US-GDP|value=3000000000|start_year=2012|r=-6|fmt=eq}}). In April 2015, Spotify began another round of fundraising, with a report from ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' stating it was seeking $400 million ({{Inflation|index=US-GDP|value=400000000|start_year=2015|r=-5|fmt=eq}}), which would value the company at $8.4 billion ({{Inflation|index=US-GDP|value=8400000000|start_year=2015|r=-6|fmt=eq}}). The financing was closed in June 2015, with Spotify raising $526 million ({{Inflation|index=US-GDP|value=526000000|start_year=2015|r=-5|fmt=eq}}), at a value of $8.53 billion ({{Inflation|index=US-GDP|value=8530000000|start_year=2015|r=-6|fmt=eq}}).<ref>ref_176</ref> In January 2016, Spotify raised another $500 million ({{Inflation|index=US-GDP|value=500000000|start_year=2016|r=-5|fmt=eq}}) through convertible bonds. In March 2016, Spotify raised $1 billion ({{Inflation|index=US-GDP|value=1000000000|start_year=2016|r=-6|fmt=eq}}) in financing by debt plus a discount of 20% on shares once the [[initial public offering]] (IPO) of shares takes place.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=MacMillan |first1=Douglas |last2=Jarzemsky |first2=Matt |last3=Farrell |first3=Maureen |date=29 March 2016 |title=Spotify Raises $1 Billion in Debt Financing |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/spotify-raises-1-billion-in-debt-financing-1459284467 |access-date=9 November 2016 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |archive-date=9 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161109075343/http://www.wsj.com/articles/spotify-raises-1-billion-in-debt-financing-1459284467 |url-status=live }}{{subscription required}}</ref> The company was, according to ''[[TechCrunch]]'', planning to launch on the [[stock market]] in 2017, but in 2017 it was seen as planning on doing the IPO in 2018 in order to "build up a better balance sheet and work on shifting its business model to improve its margins".<ref name="tc-ipo">{{Cite web |last1=Lunden |first1=Ingrid |last2=Roof |first2=Katie |date=2 February 2017 |title=Sources: Spotify may delay IPO to 2018 as it rethinks licensing deals |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/02/02/sources-spotify-may-delay-ipo-to-2018-as-it-rethinks-licensing-deals/ |access-date=12 February 2017 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |archive-date=13 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170213163644/https://techcrunch.com/2017/02/02/sources-spotify-may-delay-ipo-to-2018-as-it-rethinks-licensing-deals/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Downloads ===
In March 2009, Spotify began offering [[music download]]s in the United Kingdom, France, and Spain. Users could purchase tracks from Spotify, which partnered with [[7digital]] to incorporate the feature. The ability to purchase and download music tracks via the app was removed on 4 January 2013.<ref name="No purchase" />

=== Spotify for Artists ===
In November 2015, Spotify introduced a "Fan Insights" panel in limited [[Software release life cycle|beta]] form, letting artists and managers access data on monthly listeners, geographical data, demographic information, music preferences and more.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Dillett |first=Romain |date=17 November 2015 |title=Spotify Bets On Data To Lure Artists To Its Platform |url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/11/17/spotify-bets-on-data-to-lure-artists-to-its-platform/ |access-date=18 April 2017 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |archive-date=19 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419103135/https://techcrunch.com/2015/11/17/spotify-bets-on-data-to-lure-artists-to-its-platform/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In April 2017, the panel was upgraded to leave beta status, renamed as "Spotify for Artists", and opened to all artists and managers. Additional features include the ability to get "verified" status with a blue checkmark on an artist's profile, receiving artist support from Spotify, customising the profile page with photos and promoting a certain song as their "pick".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Perez |first=Sarah |date=18 April 2017 |title=Spotify's artist dashboard exits beta, offering streaming insights, profile management & more |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/04/18/spotifys-artist-dashboard-exits-beta-offering-streaming-insights-profile-management-more/ |access-date=18 April 2017 |website=TechCrunch |publisher=AOL |archive-date=18 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170418161500/https://techcrunch.com/2017/04/18/spotifys-artist-dashboard-exits-beta-offering-streaming-insights-profile-management-more/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Rys |first=Dan |date=18 April 2017 |title=Spotify Upgrades Fan Insights Feature to 'Spotify for Artists': Exclusive |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7761970/spotify-upgrades-fan-insights-spotify-for-artists-exclusive |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=18 April 2017 |archive-date=19 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419131250/http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7761970/spotify-upgrades-fan-insights-spotify-for-artists-exclusive |url-status=live }}</ref>

In September 2018, Spotify announced "Upload Beta", allowing artists to upload directly to the platform instead of going through a [[music industry|distributor]] or [[record label]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Deahl |first=Dani |date=20 September 2018 |title=Spotify will now let artists directly upload their music to the platform |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/9/20/17879840/spotify-artist-direct-upload-independent-music |access-date=10 April 2019 |website=The Verge |archive-date=10 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410092646/https://www.theverge.com/2018/9/20/17879840/spotify-artist-direct-upload-independent-music |url-status=live }}</ref> The feature was rolled out to a small number of US-based artists by invitation only. Uploading was free and artists received 100% of the revenue from songs they uploaded; artists were able to control when their release went public. On 1 July 2019, Spotify deprecated the program and announced plans to stop accepting direct uploads by the end of that month and eventually remove all content uploaded in this manner.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Darus |first=Alex |date=2 July 2019 |title=Spotify shuts down direct music uploading for independent artists |url=https://www.altpress.com/news/spotify-independent-artists-upload-music-streaming/ |access-date=3 July 2019 |website=Alternative Press |archive-date=6 May 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200506113149/https://www.altpress.com/news/spotify-independent-artists-upload-music-streaming/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Industry initiatives ===
In June 2017, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' reported that Spotify would announce "Secret Genius", a new initiative aimed at highlighting songwriters and producers, and the effect those people have on the music industry and the artists' careers. The project, which would feature awards, "Songshops" songwriting workshops, curated playlists, and podcasts, is an effort to "shine a light on these people behind the scenes who play such a big role in some of the most important moments of our lives. When the general public hears a song, they automatically associate it with the artist who sings it, not the people behind the scenes who make it happen, so we thought the title Secret Genius was appropriate", Spotify's former Global Head of Creator Services [[Troy Carter (talent manager)|Troy Carter]] told ''Variety'' the first awards ceremony would take place in late 2017,{{update inline|date=March 2019}} and was intended to honour "the top songwriters, producers and publishers in the industry as well as up-and-coming talent". Additionally, as part of "The Ambassador Program", 13 songwriters would each host a Songshop workshop, in which their peers would collaboratively attempt to create a hit song, with the first workshop taking place in Los Angeles in June 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Aswad |first=Jem |date=8 June 2017 |title=Spotify Launches 'Secret Genius' Program to Celebrate Songwriters (EXCLUSIVE) |url=https://variety.com/2017/music/news/exclusive-spotify-launches-secret-genius-for-songwriters-1202458229/ |access-date=9 June 2017 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-date=8 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608135636/http://variety.com/2017/music/news/exclusive-spotify-launches-secret-genius-for-songwriters-1202458229/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In October 2017, Spotify launched "Rise", a program aimed at promoting emerging artists.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Perez |first=Sarah |date=20 October 2017 |title=Spotify launches RISE, a new emerging artist program |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/10/20/spotify-launches-a-rise-a-new-emerging-artist-program/ |access-date=7 December 2017 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[Oath Inc.]] |archive-date=8 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208004119/https://techcrunch.com/2017/10/20/spotify-launches-a-rise-a-new-emerging-artist-program/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Krishna |first=Swapna |date=20 October 2017 |title=Spotify's RISE program will try to find future music superstars |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/10/20/spotify-rise-emerging-artists/ |access-date=7 December 2017 |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=Oath Inc. |archive-date=8 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208003756/https://www.engadget.com/2017/10/20/spotify-rise-emerging-artists/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In February 2020, Spotify announced it would be featuring new songwriter pages and 'written by' playlists. This was aimed at giving fans a behind the scenes look at the process of some of their favorite songwriters. Initial pages added included Justin Trantor, [[Meghan Trainor]], and [[Missy Elliott]]. Spotify thereafter announced it was planning to add more of these pages and playlists to highlight songwriters.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Spotify rolls out Written By playlists as it expands support for songwriters and publishers |url=https://www.musicweek.com/digital/read/spotify-rolls-out-written-by-playlists-as-it-expands-support-for-songwriters-and-publishers/080354 |access-date=21 July 2020 |website=www.musicweek.com |archive-date=17 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200717000027/https://www.musicweek.com/digital/read/spotify-rolls-out-written-by-playlists-as-it-expands-support-for-songwriters-and-publishers/080354 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |date=9 July 2020 |title=Spotify Adds Hundreds More Songwriter Pages and 'Written By' Playlists |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/9415812/spotify-adds-songwriter-pages-written-by-playlists |magazine=Billboard |access-date=21 July 2020 |archive-date=22 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200722060348/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/9415812/spotify-adds-songwriter-pages-written-by-playlists |url-status=live }}</ref>

In January 2021, Spotify made a selection of audiobooks available on the platform as a test of developing a greater breadth of content for users.<ref>{{Cite web |date=25 January 2021 |title=Spotify Tests Audiobooks With Classics Collection (Exclusive) |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/spotify-tests-audiobooks-with-frankenstein-jane-eyre-and-other-literary-classics-exclusive |access-date=25 January 2021 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |language=en |archive-date=25 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210125151827/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/spotify-tests-audiobooks-with-frankenstein-jane-eyre-and-other-literary-classics-exclusive |url-status=live }}</ref> The addition of audiobooks to the service would create similar offerings to that of Amazon's [[Audible (service)|Audible]]. In 2020, Spotify partnered with [[Wizarding World]] to release a series of recorded readings of ''Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone,'' by various stars of the franchise.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Carman |first=Ashley |date=5 May 2020 |title=Daniel Radcliffe and others are reading chapters of Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone on video |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/5/5/21247804/harry-potter-daniel-radcliffe-reading-philosophers-stone-spotify-video |access-date=25 January 2021 |website=The Verge |language=en |archive-date=25 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210125162056/https://www.theverge.com/2020/5/5/21247804/harry-potter-daniel-radcliffe-reading-philosophers-stone-spotify-video |url-status=live }}</ref> In November 2023, Spotify expanded free access to 200,000 audiobooks for Spotify Premium subscribers.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Vega |first=Nicolas |date=2023-11-08 |title=Spotify Premium subscribers can now listen to over 200,000 audiobooks for free |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2023/11/08/spotify-subscribers-can-now-listen-to-over-200000-audiobooks-for-free.html |access-date=2023-11-09 |website=CNBC |language=en |archive-date=9 November 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231109063502/https://www.cnbc.com/2023/11/08/spotify-subscribers-can-now-listen-to-over-200000-audiobooks-for-free.html |url-status=live }}</ref> In April 2024, Spotify expanded access to the audiobooks from the US, UK and Australia to include Canada, Ireland and New Zealand. The company also announced an expansion of its book catalogue to 250,000 books.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Malik |first1=Aisha |title=Spotify brings its audiobooks perk for Premium users to Canada, Ireland and New Zealand |url=https://techcrunch.com/2024/04/02/spotify-free-audiobooks-perk-for-premium-canada-ireland-new-zealand/ |website=TechCrunch |access-date=2 April 2024 |date=2 April 2024}}</ref>

=== Stations by Spotify ===
On 31 January 2018, Spotify started testing a new [[Pandora Radio|Pandora]]-styled standalone app called Stations by Spotify for Australian Android users.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Spotify's new Stations app is all about playlists without any of the faff |work=Alphr |url=http://www.alphr.com/spotify/1008362/spotify-stations-app-playlists |access-date=25 May 2018 |archive-date=25 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180525205237/http://www.alphr.com/spotify/1008362/spotify-stations-app-playlists |url-status=live }}</ref> It featured 62 music channels, each devoted to a particular genre. Spotify itself has two channels named after its playlists that link directly to the users' profile: "Release Radar" and "Discover Weekly". The aim was to help users to listen to the music they want without [[information overload]] or spending time building their own playlists. At launch, the skipping feature was not featured to "reinforce the feel of radio", but it was quietly added later and with no limits. Songs can be "loved" but cannot be "hated". If a song is "loved", a custom radio channel will be created based on it, and when there are at least 15 of these songs, a "My Favourites" channel is unlocked.

The standalone app was made available to all iOS and Android users in the United States since 4 June 2019.<ref>[https://www.theverge.com/2019/6/4/18651865/spotify-stations-ios-release-date-news-features-australia-playlists Spotify Stations is now available in the US] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210116231700/https://www.theverge.com/2019/6/4/18651865/spotify-stations-ios-release-date-news-features-australia-playlists/ |date=16 January 2021 }} – ''[[The Verge]]'' (published 4 June 2019)</ref>

Spotify announced the app would be shut down on 16 May 2022. The company said users would be able to login into the main Spotify app with their Stations account and transfer their stations into Spotify.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lawler |first=Richard |date=6 May 2022 |title=Spotify will shut down its radio-like listening app Stations on May 16th |url=https://www.theverge.com/2022/5/6/23060239/spotify-stations-experiment-may-16th-radio-pandora |access-date=7 May 2022 |website=The Verge |archive-date=6 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220506202340/https://www.theverge.com/2022/5/6/23060239/spotify-stations-experiment-may-16th-radio-pandora |url-status=live }}</ref>

