Spotify has client software currently available for [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[macOS]], [[Wear OS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[watchOS]], [[iPadOS]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[PlayStation 5]], [[Xbox One]] and [[Xbox Series X and Series S|Xbox Series X/S]] game consoles. There is an official, although unsupported Linux version. Spotify also offers a proprietary protocol known as "Spotify Connect", which lets users listen to music through a wide range of entertainment systems, including speakers, receivers, TVs, cars, and smartwatches. Spotify also has a web player (open.spotify.com).<ref name="Web player" /> Offline Music listening is possible on watchOS<ref>{{Cite web |title=Spotify on Apple Watch |url=https://support.spotify.com/us/article/spotify-on-apple-watch/ |access-date=6 July 2022 |website=Spotify |language=en-US |archive-date=6 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220706195443/https://support.spotify.com/us/article/spotify-on-apple-watch/ |url-status=live }}</ref> and more recently added to Google's WearOS<ref>{{Cite web |first=Chris |last=Wedel |date=2 September 2021 |title=How to use Spotify offline on Wear OS 3 watches |url=https://www.androidcentral.com/how-use-spotify-offline-wear-os-3-watches |access-date=6 July 2022 |website=Android Central |language=en |archive-date=6 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220706195443/https://www.androidcentral.com/how-use-spotify-offline-wear-os-3-watches |url-status=live }}</ref> for those with premium subscriptions. Unlike the apps, the web player does not have the ability to download music for offline listening. In June 2017, Spotify became available as an app through [[Windows Store]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Warren |first=Tom |date=20 June 2017 |title=Spotify is now available in the Windows Store |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/6/20/15840992/spotify-windows-store-app-download |access-date=20 June 2017 |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |archive-date=14 April 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210414044434/https://www.theverge.com/2017/6/20/15840992/spotify-windows-store-app-download |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Weir |first=Andy |date=20 June 2017 |title=Spotify for Windows 10 PCs appears in the Windows Store, but you can't have it... [Update: Oh yes, you can!] |url=https://www.neowin.net/news/spotify-for-windows-10-pcs-appears-in-the-windows-store-but-you-can039t-have-it-yet |access-date=20 June 2017 |website=[[Neowin]] |archive-date=20 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170620162442/https://www.neowin.net/news/spotify-for-windows-10-pcs-appears-in-the-windows-store-but-you-can039t-have-it-yet |url-status=live }}</ref>
=== Features ===
[[File:Spotify Screenshot Windows.png|alt=It is showing an album from Kevin MacLeod, and also the playlist queue, as the playlist queue is no longer fullscreen when opened. It's now a sidebar.|left|thumb|Spotify Desktop Client running on Windows]]In Spotify's apps, music can be browsed or searched for via various parameters, such as artist, album, genre, [[playlist]], or record label. Users can create, edit and share playlists, share tracks on [[social media]], and make playlists with other users. Spotify provides access to over 100 million songs, 5 million podcasts, and 4 billion playlists. In June 2012, Soundrop became the first Spotify app to attract major funding, receiving $3 million ({{Inflation|index=US-GDP|value=3000000|start_year=2012|r=-3|fmt=eq}}) from Spotify investor Northzone.<ref>{{Cite web |date=28 October 2016 |title=Spotify vs. Apple Music: Which service is the streaming king? |url=http://www.digitaltrends.com/music/apple-music-vs-spotify/ |access-date=14 November 2016 |website=[[Digital Trends]] |archive-date=7 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170107223931/http://www.digitaltrends.com/music/apple-music-vs-spotify/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Russell |first=Jon |date=2 March 2017 |title=Spotify Reaches 50 Million Paying Users |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/03/02/spotify-50-million/ |access-date=6 June 2017 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |archive-date=27 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427184514/https://techcrunch.com/2017/03/02/spotify-50-million/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Spotify company info2" />

In November 2011, Spotify introduced a Spotify Apps service that made it possible for third-party developers to design applications that could be hosted within the Spotify computer software. The applications provided features such as synchronised lyrics, music reviews, and song recommendations.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Dredge |first=Stuart |date=30 November 2011 |title=Spotify amps up iTunes rivalry with its own apps platform |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/appsblog/2011/nov/30/spotify-apps-platform |access-date=8 November 2016 |website=The Guardian |archive-date=6 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206124143/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/appsblog/2011/nov/30/spotify-apps-platform |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Cheredar |first=Tom |date=12 June 2012 |title=Even Spotify apps are getting funded: Soundrop raises $3M to turn music social |url=https://venturebeat.com/2012/06/12/soundrop/ |access-date=8 November 2016 |website=[[VentureBeat]] |archive-date=10 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161110034410/http://venturebeat.com/2012/06/12/soundrop/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Lunden |first=Ingrid |date=11 June 2012 |title=Spotify App Soundrop Tunes Into First Investment: $3M From Spotify Lead Backer Northzone |url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/06/11/spotify-app-soundrop-tunes-into-first-investment-3m-from-spotify-lead-backer-northzone/ |access-date=8 November 2016 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |archive-date=9 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161109083916/https://techcrunch.com/2012/06/11/spotify-app-soundrop-tunes-into-first-investment-3m-from-spotify-lead-backer-northzone/ |url-status=live }}</ref> However, after the June 2014 announcement of a Web [[API]] that allowed third-party developers to integrate Spotify content in their own web applications, the company discontinued its Spotify Apps platform in October, stating that its new development tools for the Spotify web player fulfilled many of the advantages of the former Spotify Apps service that allows users to access the service directly from their web browser without downloading the app. But "would ensure the Spotify platform remained relevant and easy to develop on, as well as enabling you to build innovative and engaging music experiences".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lunden |first=Ingrid |date=13 November 2014 |title=Spotify Axes App Finder, Kills Soundrop and Its Listening Rooms |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/11/13/rip-spotify-apps-rip-soundrop/ |access-date=8 November 2016 |website=TechCrunch |publisher=AOL |archive-date=9 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161109083743/https://techcrunch.com/2014/11/13/rip-spotify-apps-rip-soundrop/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In April 2012, Spotify introduced a "Spotify Play Button", an embeddable music player that can be added to blogs, websites, or social media profiles, that lets visitors listen to a specific song, playlist, or album without leaving the page.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Constine |first=Josh |date=11 April 2012 |title=Spotify's New Embeddable Play Button Lets Any Site Turn You On To Legal Tunes |url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/04/11/spotify-play-button/ |access-date=13 November 2016 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |archive-date=13 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161113175437/https://techcrunch.com/2012/04/11/spotify-play-button/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The following November, the company began rolling out a web player, with a similar design to its computer programs, but without the requirement of any installation.<ref name="Web player">{{Cite web |last=Hamburger |first=Ellis |date=15 November 2012 |title=Spotify to begin rolling out browser-based music app in beta today |url=https://www.theverge.com/2012/11/15/3649068/spotify-browser-player-web-app |access-date=13 November 2016 |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |archive-date=11 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161111040254/http://www.theverge.com/2012/11/15/3649068/spotify-browser-player-web-app |url-status=live }}</ref>

In December 2012, Spotify introduced a "Follow" tab and a "Discover" tab,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Spotify Improves Music Discovery, Social Features |url=https://abcnews.go.com/blogs/technology/2012/12/spotify-improves-music-discovery-social-features |access-date=17 July 2023 |website=ABC News |archive-date=17 July 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230717204536/https://abcnews.go.com/blogs/technology/2012/12/spotify-improves-music-discovery-social-features |url-status=live }}</ref> along with a "Collection" section.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Spotify Launches Influencer Following Music Graph, Collection, And Instant Previews To Aid Discovery |url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/12/06/spotify-following/ |access-date=17 July 2023 |website=TechCrunch |date=6 December 2012 |archive-date=17 July 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230717204545/https://techcrunch.com/2012/12/06/spotify-following/ |url-status=live }}</ref> "Follow" lets users follow artists and friends to see what they are listening to, while "Discover" directs users to new releases as well as music, review, and concert recommendations based on listening history. Users can add tracks to a "Collection" section of the app, rather than adding them to a specific playlist.<ref name="verge-collection">{{Cite web |last=Hamburger |first=Ellis |date=6 December 2012 |title=Spotify debuts new Discovery engine, Collection, and Follow, which lets users follow friends and celebrities |url=https://www.theverge.com/2012/12/6/3736018/spotify-debuts-new-discovery-engine-collection-and-follow-which-lets |access-date=6 June 2017 |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |archive-date=24 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224200904/http://www.theverge.com/2012/12/6/3736018/spotify-debuts-new-discovery-engine-collection-and-follow-which-lets |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Warren |first=Christina |date=6 December 2012 |title=Spotify Wants to Make Music Discovery Truly Social |url=http://mashable.com/2012/12/06/spotify-social-discovery/ |access-date=6 June 2017 |website=[[Mashable]] |archive-date=26 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170526104115/http://mashable.com/2012/12/06/spotify-social-discovery/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The features were announced by CEO Daniel Ek at a press conference, with Ek saying that a common user complaint about the service was that "Spotify is great when you know what music you want to listen to, but not when you don't".<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Lanxon |first=Nate |date=6 December 2012 |title=Spotify announces major updates to service, gets Metallica catalogue |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-12/06/spotify |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121209203636/http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-12/06/spotify |archive-date=9 December 2012 |access-date=9 November 2016}}</ref>

In May 2015, Spotify announced a new "Home" start-page that could recommend music. The company also introduced "Spotify Running", a feature aimed at improving music while running with music matched to running tempo, and announced that [[podcast]]s and videos ("entertainment, news and clips") would be coming to Spotify, along with "Spotify Originals" content.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Welch |first=Chris |date=20 May 2015 |title=Spotify now does videos and podcasts |url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/5/20/8629335/spotify-adds-podcasts-videos |access-date=9 November 2016 |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |archive-date=10 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161110105539/http://www.theverge.com/2015/5/20/8629335/spotify-adds-podcasts-videos |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Moynihan |first=Tim |date=20 May 2017 |title=Here are all the new features packed inside Spotify |url=https://www.wired.com/2015/05/new-features-packed-inside-spotify/ |journal=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |access-date=6 June 2017 |archive-date=22 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222124042/https://www.wired.com/2015/05/new-features-packed-inside-spotify/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Crook |first=Jordan |date=20 May 2015 |title=Spotify Introduces Video Clips, Podcasts, And Activity-Based Playlists |url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/05/20/spotify-introduces-video-clips-podcasts-and-activity-based-playlists/ |access-date=6 June 2017 |website=TechCrunch |publisher=AOL |archive-date=7 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170707124137/https://techcrunch.com/2015/05/20/spotify-introduces-video-clips-podcasts-and-activity-based-playlists/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In December 2015, Spotify debuted [[Spotify Wrapped]], a program that creates playlists based on each user's most listened-to songs from the year. Users then can view and save this playlist at the end of the year.<ref>{{Cite web |date=7 December 2020 |title=How Spotify Wrapped Has Evolved Over The Years |url=https://screenrant.com/spotify-wrapped-stats-features-evolution/ |access-date=5 April 2021 |website=ScreenRant |language=en-US |archive-date=20 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211120201821/https://screenrant.com/spotify-wrapped-stats-features-evolution/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Swant |first=Marty |title=Spotify Rolls Out New 'Wrapped' Campaign To Help Users Remember Their Decade Of Music |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/martyswant/2019/12/17/spotify-rolls-out-new-wrapped-campaign-help-users-remember-their-decade-of-music/ |access-date=5 April 2021 |website=Forbes |language=en |archive-date=15 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211115214658/https://www.forbes.com/sites/martyswant/2019/12/17/spotify-rolls-out-new-wrapped-campaign-help-users-remember-their-decade-of-music/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In January 2016, Spotify and music annotation service [[Genius (website)|Genius]] formed a partnership, bringing annotation information from Genius into infocards presented while songs are playing in Spotify. The functionality is limited to selected playlists and was only available on Spotify's iOS app at launch,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lunden |first=Ingrid |date=12 January 2016 |title=Spotify And Genius Team To Stream The Backstory On Music Tracks |url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/01/12/spotify-teams-with-genius-to-annotate-music-tracks/ |access-date=30 March 2017 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |archive-date=31 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170331031342/https://techcrunch.com/2016/01/12/spotify-teams-with-genius-to-annotate-music-tracks/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Kulwin |first=Noah |date=12 January 2016 |title=Spotify Adds 'Behind the Lyrics' Playlists, Powered by Lyrics Site Genius |url=https://www.recode.net/2016/1/12/11588702/spotify-adds-behind-the-lyrics-playlists-powered-by-lyrics-site-genius |access-date=30 March 2017 |website=[[Recode]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |archive-date=31 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170331025550/https://www.recode.net/2016/1/12/11588702/spotify-adds-behind-the-lyrics-playlists-powered-by-lyrics-site-genius |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Cox |first=Jamieson |date=12 January 2016 |title=Spotify and Genius are collaborating on info-rich Behind the Lyrics playlists |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/1/12/10750990/spotify-genius-behind-the-lyrics-playlists-iphone |access-date=30 March 2017 |website=[[The Verge]] |archive-date=31 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170331030056/http://www.theverge.com/2016/1/12/10750990/spotify-genius-behind-the-lyrics-playlists-iphone |url-status=live }}</ref> being expanded to the Android app in April 2017. This feature was known as "Behind the Lyrics".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Perez |first=Sarah |date=25 April 2017 |title=Spotify brings "Behind the Lyrics" to Android |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/04/25/spotify-brings-its-behind-the-lyrics-annotations-to-android/ |access-date=25 April 2017 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |archive-date=25 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170425172230/https://techcrunch.com/2017/04/25/spotify-brings-its-behind-the-lyrics-annotations-to-android/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Dalton |first=Andrew |date=25 April 2017 |title=Spotify took its sweet time getting Behind the Lyrics on Android |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/04/25/spotify-behind-the-lyrics-on-android/ |access-date=25 April 2017 |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=AOL |archive-date=25 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170425214452/https://www.engadget.com/2017/04/25/spotify-behind-the-lyrics-on-android/ |url-status=live }}</ref> {{As of|2021|11|18|post=,}} "Behind the Lyrics" has been replaced with auto-generated real-time lyrics due to consumer demand. The feature is powered by lyrics provider Musixmatch.<ref>[https://techcrunch.com/2021/11/18/spotify-finally-rolls-out-real-time-lyrics-to-global-users/ Spotify finally rolls out real-time lyrics to global users] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220327064001/https://techcrunch.com/2021/11/18/spotify-finally-rolls-out-real-time-lyrics-to-global-users/ |date=27 March 2022 }} – ''TechCrunch'' (published 18 November 2021)</ref>

In May 2017, Spotify introduced Spotify Codes for its mobile apps, a way for users to share specific artists, tracks, playlists or albums with other people. Users find the relevant content to share and press a "soundwave-style barcode" on the display. A camera icon in the apps' search fields lets other users point their device's camera at the code, which takes them to the same content.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Garun |first=Natt |date=5 May 2017 |title=Spotify adds QR-like codes for quick music sharing |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/5/5/15562198/spotify-scannable-codes-music-sharing-mobile |access-date=6 May 2017 |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |archive-date=5 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170505223120/https://www.theverge.com/2017/5/5/15562198/spotify-scannable-codes-music-sharing-mobile |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Constine |first=Josh |date=5 May 2017 |title=Scan these new QR-style Spotify Codes to instantly play a song |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/05/05/spotify-codes/ |access-date=6 May 2017 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |archive-date=6 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170506075451/https://techcrunch.com/2017/05/05/spotify-codes/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Clark |first=Bryan |date=5 May 2017 |title=Spotify Codes bring Snapchat-like QR codes to music streaming |url=https://thenextweb.com/insider/2017/05/05/spotify-codes-bring-snapchat-like-qr-codes-to-music-streaming/ |access-date=6 May 2017 |website=The Next Web |archive-date=6 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170506092243/https://thenextweb.com/insider/2017/05/05/spotify-codes-bring-snapchat-like-qr-codes-to-music-streaming/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In January 2019, Spotify introduced Car View for Android, allowing devices running Android to have a compact Now Playing screen when the device is connected to a car's Bluetooth.<ref>{{Cite web |date=18 January 2019 |title=[Update: Rolling out as 'Car View'] Spotify tests stripped-down "Safety Mode" UI when connected to Bluetooth devices |url=https://www.xda-developers.com/spotify-safety-mode-ui-bluetooth/ |access-date=19 January 2019 |website=xda-developers |archive-date=19 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121150/https://www.xda-developers.com/spotify-safety-mode-ui-bluetooth/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Welch |first=Chris |date=16 January 2019 |title=Spotify launches a simplified Car View for controlling your music while driving |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/1/16/18185644/spotify-car-view-now-testing-android-simple-controls |access-date=19 January 2019 |website=The Verge |archive-date=19 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119174208/https://www.theverge.com/2019/1/16/18185644/spotify-car-view-now-testing-android-simple-controls |url-status=live }}</ref> Also in January 2019, Spotify beta-tested its Canvas feature, where artists or labels can upload looping 3 to 8-second moving visuals to their tracks, replacing album covers in the "Now Playing" view; users have the option to turn off this feature. Canvas is only available for Spotify's iOS and Android mobile apps.<ref>[https://www.hypebot.com/hypebot/2019/01/with-spotify-canvas-artists-can-add-moving-visuals-to-tracks.html With Spotify Canvas, Artists Add Moving Visuals To Tracks] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190202001457/https://www.hypebot.com/hypebot/2019/01/with-spotify-canvas-artists-can-add-moving-visuals-to-tracks.html |date=2 February 2019 }} – Hyperbot.com (published 31 January 2019)</ref> Months later, Spotify tested its own version of stories (the sharing format popularized by social apps) known as "Storyline", and the focus is on allowing artists to share their own insights, inspiration, details about their creative process or other meanings behind the music.<ref>[https://techcrunch.com/2019/05/13/spotify-is-testing-its-own-version-of-stories-called-storyline/ Spotify is testing its own version of Stories called 'Storyline'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220223173042/https://techcrunch.com/2019/05/13/spotify-is-testing-its-own-version-of-stories-called-storyline/ |date=23 February 2022 }} – ''TechCrunch'' (published 13 May 2019)</ref>

In March 2021, Spotify announced an upcoming option for higher-resolution sound, Spotify Hi-Fi.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Richardson |first=Mark |date=8 March 2021 |title=Streaming for Audiophiles |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/streaming-for-audiophiles-11615243830?mod=tech_lista_pos2 |access-date=11 March 2021 |archive-date=10 March 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210310230149/https://www.wsj.com/articles/streaming-for-audiophiles-11615243830?mod=tech_lista_pos2 |url-status=live }}</ref>

==== Playlists and discovery ====
In July 2015, Spotify launched Discover Weekly, a playlist generated weekly. Updated on Mondays, it provides users with music recommendations.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Kokalitcheva |first=Kia |date=20 July 2015 |title=Spotify's new feature will help you fight the Monday blues |url=http://fortune.com/2015/07/20/spotify-discovery-playlists/ |access-date=6 June 2017 |website=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |archive-date=26 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180126012656/http://fortune.com/2015/07/20/spotify-discovery-playlists/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Dredge |first=Stuart |date=20 July 2015 |title=Spotify bites back at Apple Music with weekly 'mixtape' playlist for each user |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/jul/20/spotify-apple-music-weekly-mixtape-playlist |access-date=6 June 2017 |website=[[The Guardian]] |archive-date=25 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180125193700/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/jul/20/spotify-apple-music-weekly-mixtape-playlist |url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2015, ''[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]]'' reported that songs in Discover Weekly playlists had been streamed 1.7 billion times.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Pasick |first=Adam |date=21 December 2015 |title=The magic that makes Spotify's Discover Weekly playlists so damn good |url=http://qz.com/571007/the-magic-that-makes-spotifys-discover-weekly-playlists-so-damn-good/ |access-date=11 December 2016 |website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]] |archive-date=3 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203090004/http://qz.com/571007/the-magic-that-makes-spotifys-discover-weekly-playlists-so-damn-good/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

In March 2016, Spotify launched six playlists branded as Fresh Finds, including the main playlist and Fire Emoji, Basement, Hiptronix, Six Strings, and Cyclone (hip-hop, electronic, pop, guitar-driven, and experimental music respectively). The playlists spotlight songs by lesser-known musicians and their songs.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Spotify now has even more playlists to help you find hot new music |work=Business Insider |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/spotify-introduces-fresh-finds-playlists-2016-3 |access-date=10 June 2018 |archive-date=12 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612143123/http://www.businessinsider.com/spotify-introduces-fresh-finds-playlists-2016-3 |url-status=live}}</ref>

In August 2016, Spotify launched Release Radar, a personalized playlist that allows users to stay up-to-date on new music released by the artists they listen to the most. It also helps users discover new music, by mixing in other artists' music. The playlist is updated every Friday, and is a maximum of two hours in length.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Popper |first=Ben |date=5 August 2016 |title=Spotify's Release Radar is a personalized playlist of brand-new music |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/8/5/12380816/spotify-release-radar-personalized-discovery-curation |access-date=15 March 2017 |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |archive-date=15 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315175313/http://www.theverge.com/2016/8/5/12380816/spotify-release-radar-personalized-discovery-curation |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Constine |first=Josh |date=5 August 2016 |title=Spotify follows Discover Weekly with personalized new releases playlist |url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/08/05/spotify-release-radar/ |access-date=15 March 2017 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |archive-date=15 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315174825/https://techcrunch.com/2016/08/05/spotify-release-radar/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

The RADAR program is Spotify's global artist program, exclusively designed to help emerging artists worldwide reach the next stage in their careers and strengthen their connection to listeners. {{citation needed|date=February 2022}}

Spotify provides artists taking part in RADAR with resources and access to integrated marketing opportunities to help them boost their careers, in addition to expanded reach and exposure to 178 markets worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web |date=30 May 2021 |title=The Tea with AleXa: An Exclusive Interview with the K-Pop Sensation! |url=https://www.el-shai.com/alexa-exclusive-interview-with-the-k-pop-sensation/ |access-date=3 October 2021 |website=El-Shai |language=en-US |archive-date=3 October 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211003200112/https://www.el-shai.com/alexa-exclusive-interview-with-the-k-pop-sensation/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

In September 2016, Spotify introduced Daily Mix, a series of (up to six) playlists that mixes the user's favorite tracks with new, recommended songs. New users can access Daily Mix after approximately two weeks of listening to music through Spotify. Daily Mixes were only available on the Android and iOS mobile apps at launch, but the feature was later expanded to Spotify's computer app in December 2016.{{citation needed|date=February 2022}}

In 2017, Spotify introduced RapCaviar, a hip-hop playlist.<ref>{{Cite web |date=19 July 2019 |title=Apple Music takes on Spotify's influential RapCaviar brand with Rap Life playlist and weekly show |url=https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/apple-music-takes-on-spotifys-influential-rapcaviar-with-rap-life-playlist-and-weekly-show/ |website=Music Business Worldwide |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-date=17 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017204736/https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/apple-music-takes-on-spotifys-influential-rapcaviar-with-rap-life-playlist-and-weekly-show/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Marks |first=Craig |date=September 2017 |title=How a Hit Happens Now |url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/09/spotify-rapcaviar-most-influential-playlist-in-music.html |access-date=28 April 2020 |website=Vulture |archive-date=24 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200424040604/https://www.vulture.com/2017/09/spotify-rapcaviar-most-influential-playlist-in-music.html |url-status=live}}</ref> Rap Caviar had 10.9 million followers by 2019, becoming one of Spotify's Top 5 playlists.<ref>{{Cite web |date=9 February 2018 |title=What is Rap Caviar on Spotify? |url=https://routenote.com/blog/rap-caviar-spotify/ |access-date=23 September 2020 |archive-date=22 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201022062810/https://routenote.com/blog/rap-caviar-spotify/ |url-status=live}}</ref> RapCaviar was originally curated by Tuma Basa.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Meet Tuma Basa, The Mastermind Behind Spotify's 'Rap Caviar' Playlist |url=https://genius.com/a/meet-tuma-basa-the-mastermind-behind-spotify-s-rap-caviar-playlist |website=Genius |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-date=12 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712033918/https://genius.com/a/meet-tuma-basa-the-mastermind-behind-spotify-s-rap-caviar-playlist |url-status=live}}</ref> It was relaunched by Carl Chery in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Spotify sculpts Cardi B, other hip-hop stars for latest RapCaviar pantheon |url=https://www.marketingdive.com/news/spotify-sculpts-cardi-b-other-hip-hop-stars-for-latest-rapcaviar-pantheon/551795/ |website=Marketing Dive |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-date=18 June 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200618180111/https://www.marketingdive.com/news/spotify-sculpts-cardi-b-other-hip-hop-stars-for-latest-rapcaviar-pantheon/551795/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

In July 2018, Spotify introduced a beta feature that gives artists, labels, and teams an easy way to submit unreleased music directly to Spotify's editorial team for playlist consideration. {{citation needed|date=February 2022}}

In June 2019, Spotify launched a custom playlist titled "Your Daily Drive" that closely replicates the [[drive time]] format of many traditional radio stations. It combines short-form podcast news updates from ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', [[NPR]], and [[Public Radio International|PRI]] with a mix of a user's favorite songs and artists interspersed with tracks the listener has yet to discover. "Your Daily Drive", which is found in a user's library under the "Made For You" section, updates throughout the day.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/177736/spotify-launches-your-daily-drive-with-custom-music-and-news-updates/ Spotify Launches Your Daily Drive With Custom Music And News Updates] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211108082928/https://radioinsight.com/headlines/177736/spotify-launches-your-daily-drive-with-custom-music-and-news-updates/ |date=8 November 2021}} – ''Radio Insight'' (published 12 June 2019; accessed 13 June 2019)</ref>

In May 2020, Spotify introduced the Group Session feature. This feature allows two or more Premium users in the same location to share control over the music that is being played.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Clover |first=Juli |title=Spotify Gains New 'Group Session' Feature With Shared Listening Queue |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2020/05/11/spotify-adds-group-session-feature/ |access-date=12 May 2020 |website=Mac Rumors |date=11 May 2020 |archive-date=16 May 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200516191139/https://www.macrumors.com/2020/05/11/spotify-adds-group-session-feature/ |url-status=live}}</ref> The Group Session feature was later expanded to allow any Premium user to join/participate in a Group Session, with a special link the host can send to participants.<ref>{{Cite web |date=28 July 2020 |title=Your Squad Can Now Stream Simultaneously Using Spotify's Group Session Beta |url=https://newsroom.spotify.com/2020-07-28/your-squad-can-now-stream-simultaneously-using-spotifys-group-session-beta/ |access-date=10 May 2021 |website=Spotify Newsroom |language=en-US |archive-date=9 May 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210509190748/https://newsroom.spotify.com/2020-07-28/your-squad-can-now-stream-simultaneously-using-spotifys-group-session-beta/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

In July 2021, Spotify launched the "What's New" feed, a section that collects all new releases and episodes from artists and podcasts that the user follows. The feature is represented by a bell icon on the app's main page and is available on iOS and Android.<ref>{{Cite web |date=27 July 2021 |title=Spotify adds What's New feed for all the music and podcasts you follow |url=https://www.theverge.com/2021/7/27/22595581/spotify-whats-new-feed-podcasts-artists-follow |access-date=27 July 2021 |website=The Verge |language=en-US |archive-date=27 July 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210727083204/https://www.theverge.com/2021/7/27/22595581/spotify-whats-new-feed-podcasts-artists-follow |url-status=live}}</ref>

In November 2021, Spotify launched the City and Local Pulse charts, aimed at representing the songs listened to in major cities around the world. The charts are available for 200 cities with the most listeners on Spotify.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Aswad |first=Jem |date=10 November 2021 |title=Spotify Expands Charts to Include Genre and Local Categories |url=https://variety.com/2021/digital/news/spotify-charts-genre-local-1235108909/ |access-date=12 November 2021 |website=Variety |language=en-US |archive-date=24 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230124063849/https://variety.com/2021/digital/news/spotify-charts-genre-local-1235108909/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

In 2023, Spotify launched additional features to help independent artists distributing their music on the platform reach a wider array of potential fans. One such feature is a tool that Spotify rolled out in March 2023, called "Discovery Mode". Discovery Mode allows artists who meet certain criteria and have a Spotify For Artists account to submit qualifying songs for Spotify's in-house promotion services. Spotify helps place songs campaigned through Discovery Mode on listeners' personal algorithmic playlists. Discovery Mode does not require an upfront budget. Instead, a 30% commission is applied to recording royalties generated from all streams of selected songs in Discovery Mode contexts—Spotify Radio and Autoplay. All other streams of selected songs outside of Spotify Radio and Autoplay remain commission-free.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://artists.spotify.com/discovery-mode|title=Discovery Mode – Spotify for Artists|website=artists.spotify.com|access-date=11 May 2023|archive-date=11 May 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230511085126/https://artists.spotify.com/discovery-mode|url-status=live}}</ref>

In September 2023, Spotify introduced its latest playlist update 'Daylist', a new kind of playlist which adapts to the user's mood throughout the day.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Spotify rafraîchit la playlist Daylist tout au long de la journée |url=https://www.journaldugeek.com/2023/09/18/spotify-rafraichit-la-playlist-daylist-tout-au-long-de-la-journee/ |access-date=21 September 2023 |website=Journal du Geek |date=18 September 2023 |archive-date=5 March 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240305105129/https://www.journaldugeek.com/2023/09/18/spotify-rafraichit-la-playlist-daylist-tout-au-long-de-la-journee/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Spotify launches Daylist, a new kind of playlist |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/tech/spotify-daylist-launch-new-playlist-feature-b1106393.html |access-date=21 September 2023 |website=Evening Standard |date=12 September 2023 |archive-date=18 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230918182939/https://www.standard.co.uk/tech/spotify-daylist-launch-new-playlist-feature-b1106393.html |url-status=live}}</ref>

=== Listening limitations ===
Spotify has experimented with different limitations to users' listening on the Free service tier.

In April 2011, Spotify announced via a blog post that they would drastically cut the amount of music that free members could access, effective 1 May 2011. The post stated that all free members would be limited to ten hours of music streaming per month, and in addition, individual tracks were limited to five plays. New users were exempt from these changes for six months.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Butcher |first=Mike |date=14 April 2011 |title=Spotify takes the axe to its free service – can it now claim to slash music piracy? |url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/04/14/spotify-takes-the-axe-to-its-free-service-can-it-now-claim-to-slash-music-piracy/ |access-date=2 June 2017 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |archive-date=14 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170614085717/https://techcrunch.com/2011/04/14/spotify-takes-the-axe-to-its-free-service-can-it-now-claim-to-slash-music-piracy/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In March 2013, the five-play individual track limit was removed for users in the United Kingdom, and media reports stated that users in the United States, Australia, and New Zealand never had the limit in the first place.<ref>{{Cite web |last=O'Hear |first=Steve |date=19 March 2013 |title=Spotify Ditches Its 5 Play Limit For Spotify Free Users In The UK |url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/03/19/spotify-freetards/ |access-date=2 June 2017 |website=TechCrunch |publisher=AOL |archive-date=4 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704015953/https://techcrunch.com/2013/03/19/spotify-freetards/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Richmond |first=Shane |date=19 March 2013 |title=Spotify removes five-play song cap |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/news/9940432/Spotify-removes-five-play-song-cap.html |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/news/9940432/Spotify-removes-five-play-song-cap.html |archive-date=10 January 2022 |access-date=2 June 2017 |website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]}}{{cbignore}}</ref>

In December 2013, CEO Daniel Ek announced that Android and iOS smartphone users with the free service tier could listen to music in Shuffle mode, a feature in which users can stream music by specific artists and playlists without being able to pick which songs to hear. Mobile listening previously was not allowed in Spotify Free accounts. Ek stated that "We're giving people the best free music experience in the history of the smartphone."<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hamburger |first=Ellis |date=11 December 2013 |title=Spotify announces free streaming on Android and iPhone, but only in Shuffle mode |work=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/12/11/5199692/spotify-announces-free-streaming-on-android-and-iphone-but-only-in |access-date=13 November 2016 |archive-date=14 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161114175059/http://www.theverge.com/2013/12/11/5199692/spotify-announces-free-streaming-on-android-and-iphone-but-only-in |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Crook |first=Jordan |date=11 December 2013 |title=Spotify Goes Freemium On Tablets, Launches Free Shuffle Product On Smartphones |url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/12/11/spotify-launches-spotify-free-for-tablets/ |access-date=2 June 2017 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |archive-date=6 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170706130423/https://techcrunch.com/2013/12/11/spotify-launches-spotify-free-for-tablets/ |url-status=live }}</ref> This shuffle feature is not available on Android and iOS tablets, or computers.

In January 2014, Spotify removed all time limits for Free users on all platforms, including on computers, which previously had a 10-hour monthly listening limit after a 6-month grace period.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Murray-Morris |first=Sophie |date=15 January 2014 |title=Spotify removes time restrictions on free desktop player |work=[[The Independent]] |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/spotify-removes-time-restrictions-for-desktop-listening-9062361.html |url-status=live |url-access=subscription |access-date=2 June 2017 |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220524/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/spotify-removes-time-restrictions-for-desktop-listening-9062361.html |archive-date=24 May 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Constine |first=Josh |date=15 January 2014 |title=Spotify Drops Free Web Listening Time Limit Everywhere – A Big Scalability Milestone |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/01/15/spotify-limits/ |access-date=2 June 2017 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL |archive-date=15 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171115075705/https://techcrunch.com/2014/01/15/spotify-limits/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In April 2018, Spotify began to allow Free users to listen on-demand to whatever songs they want for an unlimited number of times, as long as the song is on one of the user's 15 personalized discovery playlists.<ref>{{Cite web |date=24 April 2018 |title=Spotify beefs up its free tier – TechCrunch |url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/04/24/spotify-beefs-up-its-free-tier-as-apple-music-gains-traction/ |access-date=24 April 2018 |website=techcrunch.com |archive-date=24 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424180019/https://techcrunch.com/2018/04/24/spotify-beefs-up-its-free-tier-as-apple-music-gains-traction/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Before May 2020, all service users were limited to 10,000 songs in their library, after which they would receive an "Epic collection, friend" notification and would not be able to save more music to their library.<ref name=verge-limit /> Spotify later removed this limit.<ref name=verge-limit>{{cite web |last=Gartenberg |first=Chaim |date=26 May 2020 |title=Spotify finally removes its 10,000-song library limit |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/5/26/21270409/spotify-song-library-limit-removed-music-downloads-playlists-feature |website=The Verge |access-date=1 June 2023 |archive-date=3 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230603054552/https://www.theverge.com/2020/5/26/21270409/spotify-song-library-limit-removed-music-downloads-playlists-feature |url-status=live }}</ref>

