== Criticism ==
{{Main|Criticism of Spotify}}

Spotify has attracted significant criticism since its 2006 launch.<ref name="Launch">{{Cite web |date=7 October 2008 |title=We've only just begun! |url=https://news.spotify.com/us/2008/10/07/weve-only-just-begun/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171211213512/https://news.spotify.com/us/2008/10/07/weve-only-just-begun/ |archive-date=11 December 2017 |access-date=7 November 2016 |publisher=Spotify }}</ref> The primary point of criticism centres around what artists, music creators, and the media have described as "unsustainable" compensation.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Plaugic |first=Lizzie |date=7 December 2015 |title=Spotify's Year in Music shows just how little we pay artists for their music |url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/12/7/9861372/spotify-year-in-review-artist-payment-royalties |access-date=22 January 2017 |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]]}}</ref> Unlike physical sales or legal downloads (both of which were the main medium of listening to music at the time), which pay artists a fixed amount per song or album sold, Spotify pays royalties based on their "market share": the number of streams for their songs as a proportion of total songs streamed on the service. Spotify distributes approximately 70% of its total revenue to rights-holders, who will then pay artists based on their individual agreements.<ref name="Spotify business" /> Worldwide, 30,000 musicians have joined the organization UnionOfMusicians (UMAW).<ref name="auto2">{{Cite web |title=Has Streaming Saved the Music Industry? – Tracks – Watch the full show |url=https://www.arte.tv/en/videos/100280-007-A/has-streaming-saved-the-music-industry/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211129150425/https://www.arte.tv/en/videos/100280-007-A/has-streaming-saved-the-music-industry/ |archive-date=29 November 2021 |access-date=28 October 2021 |website=ARTE }}</ref> UMAW organized protests in 31 cities in March 2021 and its campaign #JusticeAtSpotify is demanding more transparency and a compensation of one cent per stream.<ref name="auto2" />

Spotify has been criticised by artists and producers including [[Taylor Swift]] and [[Thom Yorke]], who have argued that Spotify does not fairly compensate musicians, and both withdrew their music from the service.<ref>{{Cite web |date=15 July 2013 |title=Thom Yorke pulls albums from Spotify |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-23313445 |access-date=18 January 2017 |website=BBC News |publisher=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Alter |first=Charlotte |date=3 November 2014 |title=Taylor Swift Just Removed Her Music From Spotify |url=http://time.com/3554438/taylor-swift-spotify/ |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |access-date=23 December 2016}}</ref> Their catalogues returned to the service in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Rossignol |first=Derrick |date=8 December 2017 |title=Thom Yorke's Solo Albums Are Finally Streaming On Spotify, Which He Famously Hates |url=http://uproxx.com/music/thom-yorke-spotify-streaming/ |access-date=10 December 2017 |website=[[Uproxx]] |publisher=[[Uproxx Media Group]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |date=8 June 2017 |title=Taylor Swift's Music Returning to Spotify & Other Streaming Services Tonight |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7825570/taylor-swift-spotify-streaming-again |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=9 June 2017}}</ref> While the streaming music industry in general faces the same critique about inadequate payments,<ref>{{Cite web |title=What Streaming Music Services Pay |url=http://www.informationisbeautiful.net/visualizations/spotify-apple-music-tidal-music-streaming-services-royalty-rates-compared/ |access-date=11 December 2017 |website=[[David McCandless|Information is Beautiful]]}}</ref> Spotify, being the leading service,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Singleton |first=Micah |date=15 June 2017 |title=Spotify now has 140 million active users |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/6/15/15807826/spotify-140-million-active-users |access-date=10 December 2017 |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]]}}</ref> faces particular scrutiny due to its free service tier, allowing users to listen to music for free, though with advertisements between tracks. The free service tier has led to a variety of major album releases being delayed or withdrawn from the service.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Karp |first=Hannah |date=3 December 2015 |title=Coldplay to Headline Super Bowl Halftime Show |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/coldplay-to-headline-super-bowl-halftime-show-1449174658 |access-date=24 December 2016 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Luckerson |first=Victor |date=24 November 2014 |title=Beyoncé's Latest Album Is Finally on Spotify |url=http://time.com/3602610/beyonce-spotify/ |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |access-date=24 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Carr |first=Austin |date=15 February 2012 |title=Why Spotify Turned Down Adele's ''21'' |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/1816582/why-spotify-turned-down-adeles-21 |access-date=24 December 2016 |website=[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]] |publisher=Mansueto Ventures }}</ref> In response to the allegations about unfair compensation, Spotify claims that it is benefitting the industry by migrating users away from [[Copyright infringement|unauthorized copying]] and less monetized platforms to its free service tier, and then downgrades that service until they upgrade to paid accounts.<ref name="Spotify business" /> A study has shown that [[record label]]s keep a high amount of the money earned from Spotify,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Ingham |first=Tim |date=3 February 2015 |title=Major labels keep 73% of Spotify Premium payouts – Report |url=http://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/artists-get-7-of-streaming-cash-labels-take-46/ |access-date=17 December 2016 |website=Music Business Worldwide}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Masnick |first=Mike |date=5 February 2015 |title=Yes, Major Record Labels Are Keeping Nearly All The Money They Get From Spotify, Rather Than Giving It To Artists |url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20150204/07310329906/yes-major-record-labels-are-keeping-nearly-all-money-they-get-spotify-rather-than-giving-it-to-artists.shtml |access-date=17 December 2016 |publisher=Techdirt}}</ref> and the CEO of [[Merlin Network]], a representative body for over 10,000 independent labels, has also observed significant yearly growth rates in earnings from Spotify, while clarifying that Spotify pays labels, not artists.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Buskirk |first=Eliot Van |date=21 June 2012 |title=David Lowery Might Be Right About Some Things, But He's Wrong About Streaming, Money, and Artists |url=http://evolver.fm/2012/06/21/david-lowery-might-be-right-about-some-things-but-hes-wrong-about-streaming-money-and-artists/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202073932/http://evolver.fm/2012/06/21/david-lowery-might-be-right-about-some-things-but-hes-wrong-about-streaming-money-and-artists/ |archive-date=2 December 2016 |access-date=17 December 2016 |website=Evolver.fm }}</ref> In 2017, as part of its efforts to renegotiate licence deals for an interest in [[Initial public offering|going public]], Spotify announced that artists would be able to make albums temporarily exclusive to paid subscribers if the albums are part of [[Universal Music Group]] or the Merlin Network.

In 2016, Spotify was criticized for allegedly making certain artists' music harder to find than others, as these artists would release their music to the rival streaming service [[Apple Music]] before releasing it to Spotify.<ref>{{Cite web |date=26 August 2016 |title=Spotify Is Burying Musicians for Their Apple Deals |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-08-26/spotify-said-to-retaliate-against-artists-with-apple-exclusives |access-date=22 July 2020 |website=Bloomberg.com }}</ref>

In May 2018, Spotify attracted criticism for its "Hate Content & Hateful Conduct policy" that removed the music of [[R. Kelly]] and [[XXXTentacion]] from its editorial and algorithmic playlists because "When we look at promotion, we look at issues around hateful conduct, where you have an artist or another creator who has done something off-platform that is so particularly out of line with our values, egregious, in a way that it becomes something that we don't want to associate ourselves with." R. Kelly has faced accusations of sexual abuse, while XXXTentacion was on trial for domestic abuse in a case that did not reach a judgement before [[Killing of XXXTentacion|his death]] that June.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Strauss |first=Matthew |date=10 May 2018 |title=Spotify Removes R. Kelly and XXXTentacion From Its Playlists |work=Pitchfork |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/spotify-removes-r-kelly-from-its-playlists/ |access-date=21 October 2018}}</ref> This policy was revoked in June because the company deemed the original wording to be too "vague"; they stated that "Across all genres, our role is not to regulate artists. Therefore, we are moving away from implementing a policy around artist conduct".<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Minsker |first1=Evan |last2=Yoo |first2=Noah |date=1 June 2018 |title=Spotify Walks Back Controversial "Hateful Conduct" Policy, Adds XXXTentacion to Major Playlist |work=Pitchfork |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/spotify-walks-back-controversial-hateful-conduct-policy/ |access-date=21 October 2018}}</ref> However, artists such as [[Gary Glitter]] and [[Lostprophets]] are still hidden from Spotify's radio stations.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Cairns |first1=Dan |last2=Dean |first2=Jonathan |date=27 May 2018 |title=Where will Spotify's censorship end? |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/spotify-hateful-conduct-axl-rose-r-kelly-jimmy-page-and-eminem-w890kwc3l |website=The Times }}</ref>

According to some computer science and music experts, various music communities are often ignored or overlooked by music streaming services such as Spotify.<ref name="Rolling Stone 2019">{{Cite magazine |date=4 October 2019 |title=Spotify Pivots on Global Cultures Initiative, Alarming Music Industry |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/spotify-global-cultures-initiative-892762/ |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref><ref name="Hepworth 2020">{{Cite web |last=Hepworth |first=Shelley |date=1 January 2020 |title=Streaming spells the end of the 'ownership' era of music, but are we ready to let go? |url=http://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/feb/02/streaming-spells-the-end-of-the-ownership-era-of-music-but-are-we-ready-to-let-go |access-date=18 February 2020 |website=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref name="RouteNote Blog 2020">{{Cite web |date=6 February 2020 |title=Spotify and streaming services are breaking cultural music on a worldwide stage |url=http://routenote.com/blog/spotify-and-streaming-services-are-breaking-cultural-music-on-a-worldwide-stage/ |access-date=18 February 2020 |website=RouteNote Blog}}</ref> The most commonly perceived error is said to be caused by a lack of diverse scope within curation staff, including overlooking mainstay artists in large genres, potentially causing a categorical homogenization of musical styles; even impacting mainline artists like within [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] with [[A Tribe Called Quest]].<ref name="Hepworth 2020" />

In March 2021, [[David Dayen]] argued in ''The American Prospect'' that musicians were in peril due to monopolies in streaming services like Spotify.<ref name="prospect.org">{{Cite web |last=Dayen |first=David |date=22 March 2021 |title=Islands in the Stream |url=https://prospect.org/api/content/b969aae6-89e3-11eb-a885-1244d5f7c7c6/ |website=The American Prospect}}</ref> Daniel Ek, co-founder and CEO of Spotify, discussed "what he called an artist-friendly streaming solution". He explained, "An extension of the internet radio craze of the early 2000s, Spotify would license content from record labels, and then support artists as people listened to their music."<ref name="prospect.org" />

In January 2022, 270 scientists, physicians, professors, doctors, and healthcare workers wrote an open letter to Spotify expressing concern over "false and societally harmful assertions" on [[Joe Rogan]]'s podcast, ''[[The Joe Rogan Experience]]'', and asked Spotify to "establish a clear and public policy to moderate misinformation on its platform". The 270 signatories objected to Rogan broadcasting [[COVID-19 misinformation]], citing "a highly controversial" episode featuring guest [[Robert W. Malone|Robert Malone]] (#1757).<ref>{{Cite web |last=Tapp |first=Tom |date=13 January 2022 |title=Hundreds Of Doctors Sign Open Letter Asking Spotify To Address "Mass Misinformation Events," Take Aim At Joe Rogan's Show |url=https://deadline.com/2022/01/spotify-joe-rogan-doctors-open-letter-1234909702/ |access-date=13 January 2022 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] }}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Dickson |first=E. J. |date=12 January 2022 |title='A Menace to Public Health': Doctors Demand Spotify Puts an End to Covid Lies on 'Joe Rogan Experience' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/covid-misinformation-joe-rogan-spotify-petition-1282240/ |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |access-date=13 January 2022}}</ref> On 26 January, [[Neil Young]] removed his music from Spotify after they refused to remove the podcast.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Yang |first=Maya |date=26 January 2022 |title=Spotify removes Neil Young music in feud over Joe Rogan's false Covid claims |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2022/jan/26/spotify-neil-young-joe-rogan-covid-misinformation |access-date=27 January 2022 |website=[[The Guardian]] }}</ref> Other artists and podcasters, such as [[Joni Mitchell]], [[Nils Lofgren]], [[Brené Brown]], and [[Crosby, Stills, Nash & Young|Crosby, Stills, & Nash]], also announced a boycott of Spotify.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Shafer |first=Ellise |date=28 January 2022 |title=Joni Mitchell Says She's Removing Music From Spotify: 'Irresponsible People Are Spreading Lies' |url=https://variety.com/2022/music/news/joni-mitchell-spotify-removing-music-joe-rogan-1235166691/ |website=Variety }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Repko |first=Melissa |date=30 January 2022 |title=Bruce Springsteen guitarist Nils Lofgren joins protest of Spotify over Covid misinformation |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/01/30/bruce-springsteen-guitarist-nils-lofgren-joins-spotify-boycott-.html |access-date=30 January 2022 |website=CNBC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Roth |first=Emma |date=30 January 2022 |title=Brené Brown Says She Won't Release New Episodes of Her Spotify-Exclusive Podcasts 'until Further Notice' |url=https://www.theverge.com/2022/1/30/22909140/brene-brown-spotify-podcast-joe-rogan-controversy |access-date=30 January 2022 |website=The Verge}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=David Crosby, Graham Nash and Stephen Stills ask to pull their content from Spotify |work=NPR |url=https://www.npr.org/2022/02/02/1077653424/crosby-stills-nash-young-spotify |access-date=5 February 2022}}</ref> Spotify promised to add content advisories for anything containing discussions related to COVID-19 and posted additional rules.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Roth |first=Emma |date=30 January 2022 |title=Spotify finally responds to Joe Rogan controversy with a plan to label podcasts that discuss COVID-19 |url=https://www.theverge.com/2022/1/30/22909432/spotify-covid-19-moderation-joe-rogan-vaccine-misinformation |access-date=30 January 2022 |website=The Verge}}</ref>

